## United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland

The **United Kingdom of Great Britain and Northern Ireland**, more commonly known as the **United Kingdom** or simply **Britain**, is a sovereign country situated in [Northwestern Europe](/Northwestern_Europe). It is an island nation, strategically positioned off the coast of the [European mainland](/European_mainland). Its territory is a composite of distinct geographical and political entities: [England](/England), [Scotland](/Scotland), [Wales](/Wales), and [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland). As of 2024, its population exceeds 69 million individuals. The UK’s dominion encompasses the entirety of the island of [Great Britain](/Great_Britain), the northeastern portion of the island of [Ireland](/Ireland), and a scattering of smaller islands within the archipelago known as the [British Isles](/British_Isles). Its total land area spans 94,354 square miles (244,376 km²).

The United Kingdom shares a single land border with the [Republic of Ireland](/Republic_of_Ireland). Otherwise, it is embraced by the vast expanse of the [Atlantic Ocean](/Atlantic_Ocean), the North Sea, the [English Channel](/English_Channel), the [Celtic Sea](/Celtic_Sea), and the [Irish Sea](/Irish_Sea). Furthermore, it maintains sovereignty over a collection of [British Overseas Territories](/British_Overseas_Territories) and [Crown Dependencies](/Crown_Dependencies), extending its influence beyond the immediate geographical confines. The capital and largest urban centre, not only of England but also of the United Kingdom as a whole, is [London](/London). The other national capitals – [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh), [Cardiff](/Cardiff), and [Belfast](/Belfast) – serve as the administrative hearts of Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland, respectively.

The history of human habitation within the territory that now constitutes the United Kingdom stretches back to the [Neolithic](/Neolithic) period. A significant milestone was the [Roman conquest of Britain](/Roman_conquest_of_Britain) in AD 43. The subsequent departure of the Romans ushered in an era of [Anglo-Saxon settlement](/Anglo-Saxon_settlement_of_Britain), fundamentally reshaping the cultural and linguistic landscape. The [Norman conquest of England](/Norman_conquest_of_England) in 1066 marked another pivotal moment, introducing a new aristocracy and feudal system. Following the conclusion of the [Wars of the Roses](/Wars_of_the_Roses), the [Kingdom of England](/Kingdom_of_England) experienced a period of consolidation and expansion, culminating in the [annexation of Wales](/Laws_in_Wales_Acts_1535_and_1542) and the burgeoning influence of the [British Empire](/British_Empire) by the 16th century. The 17th century witnessed a significant curtailment of the [British monarchy](/British_monarchy)'s power, notably as a consequence of the [English Civil War](/English_Civil_War). A transformative event occurred in 1707 with the [Treaty of Union](/Treaty_of_Union), which formally united the Kingdom of England and the [Kingdom of Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) to establish the [Kingdom of Great Britain](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain). During the [Georgian era](/Georgian_era), the office of [prime minister](/Prime_minister_of_the_United_Kingdom) began to solidify its position within the political structure. The [Acts of Union 1800](/Acts_of_Union_1800) further expanded the union, incorporating the [Kingdom of Ireland](/Kingdom_of_Ireland) to create the [United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland](/United_Kingdom_of_Great_Britain_and_Ireland) in 1801. However, the [partition of Ireland](/Partition_of_Ireland) in 1922, leading to the secession of most of Ireland as the [Irish Free State](/Irish_Free_State), necessitated a renaming. The [Royal and Parliamentary Titles Act 1927](/Royal_and_Parliamentary_Titles_Act_1927) officially established the present-day United Kingdom.

The UK's historical trajectory is marked by its pioneering role in the [History of industrialisation](/History_of_industrialisation). For a significant portion of the 19th and early 20th centuries, it held the position of the world's foremost global power, particularly during the era of [Pax Britannica](/Pax_Britannica) (1815–1914). The British Empire, bolstered by its [agricultural prosperity](/British_Agricultural_Revolution), its dominance in [trading nation](/Trading_nation) activities, formidable industrial capacity, groundbreaking [significant technological achievements](/List_of_British_innovations_and_discoveries_in_the_19th_century), and the rise of [19th-century London](/19th-century_London) as a global financial hub, was the preeminent [economic power](/Economic_power) throughout the 19th century. At its zenith in the 1920s, the empire spanned nearly a quarter of the Earth's landmass and population, making it the [largest empire in history](/List_of_largest_empires). Nevertheless, the immense strain of [its involvement in the First World War](/History_of_the_United_Kingdom_during_the_First_World_War) and [the Second World War](/Military_history_of_the_United_Kingdom_during_World_War_II) significantly eroded [Britain's economic power](/Economy_of_the_British_Empire). This, coupled with a global surge in [decolonisation](/Decolonisation), ultimately led to the independence of most of its colonies.

The United Kingdom operates as a [constitutional monarchy](/Constitutional_monarchy) and a [parliamentary democracy](/Parliamentary_democracy). Its governance is structured around three distinct legal jurisdictions: [England and Wales](/English_law), [Scotland](/Scots_law), and [Northern Ireland](/Law_of_Northern_Ireland). Each of these jurisdictions possesses its own devolved governments and parliaments, which exercise authority over a range of designated [devolved](/Devolution_in_the_United_Kingdom) matters. The UK is classified as a [developed country](/Developed_country) with a highly [advanced economy](/Economy_of_the_United_Kingdom). It consistently ranks among the [largest economies by nominal GDP](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)) and stands as one of the world's principal exporters and importers. As a [nuclear state](/Nuclear_state) possessing one of the [highest defence budgets](/List_of_countries_by_military_expenditures), the UK maintains a formidable military presence in Europe. Its global influence extends through [soft power](/Anglicisation), evident in the legal and political frameworks adopted by many of [its former colonies](/List_of_countries_that_have_gained_independence_from_the_United_Kingdom). Moreover, [British culture](/Culture_of_the_United_Kingdom), particularly in areas such as [language](/English-speaking_world), [literature](/British_literature), [music](/Music_of_the_United_Kingdom), and [sport](/Sport_in_the_United_Kingdom), continues to exert a significant global impact. The UK is recognized as a [great power](/Great_power) and actively participates in numerous international organizations and forums, shaping global discourse and policy.

