### History

#### Prior to the Treaty of Union

The earliest evidence of human settlement in the territory that would become the United Kingdom dates back to approximately 30,000 years ago, with [Cro-Magnons](/Cro-Magnons) arriving in successive waves. Continuous habitation, however, is only established from around 11,500 years ago, following the last glacial retreat. By the close of the [prehistoric period](/Prehistoric_Britain), the inhabitants are believed to have largely belonged to a culture identified as [Insular Celtic](/Insular_Celts), encompassing both [Brittonic Britain](/Britons_(historical)) and [Gaelic Ireland](/Gaelic_Ireland).

The [Roman conquest](/Roman_conquest_of_Britain), commencing in AD 43, established a 400-year period of [Roman Britain](/Roman_Britain) in the southern part of the island. This was followed by the arrival of [Germanic](/Germanic_peoples) [Anglo-Saxon](/Anglo-Saxon) settlers, who significantly reduced the Brittonic-speaking territories to areas that would later become [Wales](/Wales), [Cornwall](/Cornwall), and, for a period, the [Hen Ogledd](/Hen_Ogledd) in northern England and southern Scotland. The majority of the territory settled by the Anglo-Saxons eventually coalesced into the unified Kingdom of England by the 10th century. Simultaneously, [Gaelic speakers in north-west Britain](/D%C3%A1l_Riata), believed to have migrated from northeastern Ireland around the 5th century, allied with the [Picts](/Picts) to form the [Kingdom of Scotland](/Kingdom_of_Scotland) in the 9th century.

The [Norman conquest of England](/Norman_conquest_of_England) in 1066 introduced significant changes. The Normans, upon conquering England, extended their influence into [large parts of Wales](/Norman_invasion_of_Wales), subjugated much of [Ireland](/Norman_invasion_of_Ireland), and were invited to settle in Scotland. This influx brought feudalism, modelled on Northern French systems, and [Norman-French](/Norman-French) culture to these lands. The [Anglo-Norman](/Anglo-Normans) ruling class, while profoundly influential, eventually assimilated into the local cultures. Subsequent medieval English monarchs completed the [conquest of Wales](/Conquest_of_Wales) and made repeated, though ultimately unsuccessful, attempts to annex Scotland. Scotland, through the assertion of its independence in the 1320 [Declaration of Arbroath](/Declaration_of_Arbroath), managed to maintain its autonomy, albeit amidst near-constant conflict with England, known as the [Anglo-Scottish Wars](/Anglo-Scottish_Wars).

A landmark document in the development of governance was [Magna Carta](/Magna_Carta), signed in 1215. It established the principle that no government is above the law and guaranteed certain rights to citizens. English monarchs, through their extensive landholdings in France and claims to the French throne, were deeply involved in conflicts on the continent, most notably the [Hundred Years' War](/Hundred_Years%27_War). During this period, the [Kings of Scots](/List_of_Scottish_monarchs) maintained an alliance with France, known as the [Auld Alliance](/Auld_Alliance).

The [early modern period](/Early_modern_Britain) in Britain was characterized by religious upheaval stemming from the [Reformation](/Reformation). This led to the establishment of Protestant state churches in each kingdom. The [English Reformation](/English_Reformation) in the 16th century initiated profound political, constitutional, social, and cultural transformations, solidifying the [Church of England](/Church_of_England) and shaping a distinct English national identity. Wales was fully integrated into the Kingdom of England through the [Laws in Wales Acts 1535 and 1542](/Laws_in_Wales_Acts_1535_and_1542), and Ireland was constituted as a kingdom in personal union with the English crown. In what would become Northern Ireland, the lands of the independent Catholic Gaelic nobility were confiscated and redistributed to Protestant settlers from England and Scotland as part of the [Plantation of Ulster](/Plantation_of_Ulster).

The [Bayeux Tapestry](/Bayeux_Tapestry) vividly depicts the [Battle of Hastings](/Battle_of_Hastings) in 1066 and the events leading up to it.

#### Union of England and Scotland

A pivotal moment in the formation of the modern UK occurred on 1 May 1707, with the [Acts of Union 1707](/Acts_of_Union_1707) uniting the Kingdom of England and the Kingdom of Scotland to form the Kingdom of Great Britain. The 18th century saw the gradual development of cabinet government under the leadership of [Robert Walpole](/Robert_Walpole), who effectively served as the first prime minister from 1721 to 1742. This era was also marked by a series of [Jacobite uprisings](/Jacobite_uprisings), attempts to dethrone the Protestant [House of Hanover](/House_of_Hanover) and reinstate the Catholic [House of Stuart](/House_of_Stuart). The final Jacobite defeat at the [Battle of Culloden](/Battle_of_Culloden) in 1746 led to the forceful assimilation of the [Scottish Highlanders](/Scottish_Highlanders) into Scottish society, with the revocation of the feudal independence of [clan chiefs](/Scottish_clan_chief). Meanwhile, British colonial ambitions expanded towards Asia, particularly [India](/India), following the loss of its North American colonies, which declared independence in the [American War of Independence](/American_Revolutionary_War), establishing the [United States](/United_States).

British merchants were instrumental in the [Atlantic slave trade](/Atlantic_slave_trade), primarily between 1662 and 1807. During this period, British and colonial [slave ships](/Slave_ships) transported approximately 3.3 million enslaved Africans to work on [plantations](/Plantation_economy) in the Caribbean and North America. However, driven by the burgeoning [abolitionist movement](/Abolitionism_in_the_United_Kingdom), Parliament enacted legislation to ban the slave trade in 1807, followed by the abolition of slavery throughout the British Empire in 1833. Britain then assumed a leading role in the global movement to eradicate slavery, employing measures such as the [blockade of Africa](/Blockade_of_Africa) and diplomatic pressure on other nations through a series of treaties.

#### United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland

The year 1800 saw the parliaments of Great Britain and Ireland enact Acts of Union, uniting the two kingdoms and establishing the United Kingdom of Great Britain and Ireland on 1 January 1801. The defeat of France at the conclusion of the [French Revolutionary Wars](/French_Revolutionary_Wars) and [Napoleonic Wars](/Napoleonic_Wars) (1792–1815) positioned the United Kingdom as the preeminent global naval and imperial power. By approximately 1830, London had become the [largest city in the world](/List_of_largest_cities_throughout_history). With [unchallenged dominance at sea](/History_of_the_Royal_Navy_(after_1707)), British global influence during the period of [Pax Britannica](/Pax_Britannica) (1815–1914) was characterized by [relative peace amongst the great powers](/International_relations_of_the_Great_Powers_(1814%E2%80%931919)). During this era, the British Empire became the global [hegemon](/Hegemon) and effectively assumed the role of [global policeman](/Global_policeman). Britain participated in the [Crimean War](/Crimean_War) (1853–1856) as an ally of the [Ottoman Empire](/Ottoman_Empire) against [Tsarist Russia](/Russian_Empire). Following the [Indian Rebellion of 1857](/Indian_Rebellion_of_1857), the British government, under [Lord Palmerston](/Henry_John_Temple,_3rd_Viscount_Palmerston), assumed [direct rule](/Direct_rule) over [India](/British_Raj). Beyond its formal colonial control, Britain's extensive global trade network allowed it to [effectively control](/Informal_empire) the economies of regions such as [East Asia](/East_Asia) and [Latin America](/Latin_America).

Throughout the [Victorian era](/Victorian_era) (1837–1901), political sentiment favoured [free trade](/Free_trade) and [laissez-faire](/Laissez-faire) economic policies. Beginning with the [Great Reform Act](/Great_Reform_Act) in 1832, Parliament progressively expanded the [voting franchise](/Reform_Acts), with the [1884 Reform Act](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_1884), championed by [William Gladstone](/William_Ewart_Gladstone), granting suffrage to a majority of males for the first time. The British population experienced rapid growth, accompanied by significant [urbanisation](/Urbanisation), leading to considerable social and economic pressures. By the late 19th century, the [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), under leaders like [Benjamin Disraeli](/Benjamin_Disraeli) and [Lord Salisbury](/Robert_Gascoyne-Cecil,_3rd_Marquess_of_Salisbury), initiated a phase of [imperial expansion in Africa](/Scramble_for_Africa). This period also saw a policy of "[splendid isolation](/Splendid_isolation)" in European affairs and efforts to counter the influence of the [Russian Empire](/Russian_Empire) in [Afghanistan](/Emirate_of_Afghanistan) and [Persia](/Qajar_Iran), a geopolitical rivalry known as the [Great Game](/Great_Game). During this time, [Canada](/Canada), [Australia](/Australia), and [New Zealand](/New_Zealand) were granted self-governing [dominion](/Dominion) status. As the 20th century dawned, Britain's industrial preeminence faced increasing competition from the [German Empire](/German_Empire) and the [United States](/United_States). The [Edwardian era](/Edwardian_era) (1901–1910) was characterized by significant [social reform](/Liberal_welfare_reforms) and the growing prominence of [home rule for Ireland](/Irish_Home_Rule_movement) as domestic political issues. The [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK)) emerged in 1900 from an alliance of [trade unions](/Trade_unions_in_the_United_Kingdom) and smaller socialist organizations, while the [suffragettes](/Suffragettes) actively campaigned for women's suffrage.

#### World Wars and Partition of Ireland

Britain played a crucial role as one of the principal [Allies](/Allies_of_World_War_I) in the defeat of the [Central Powers](/Central_Powers) in [First World War](/First_World_War) (1914–1918). Alongside its allies, including France, Russia, and later the United States, British forces engaged in extensive campaigns across the British Empire and various European theaters, most notably on the [Western Front](/Western_Front_(World_War_I)). The devastating casualties incurred through [trench warfare](/Trench_warfare) resulted in the loss of a significant portion of a generation of men, leaving lasting social scars and profound societal disruption. Britain sustained 2.5 million casualties and concluded the war burdened by a substantial national debt.

The ramifications of the war prompted the government to expand suffrage through the [Representation of the People Act 1918](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_1918), granting the right to vote in national and local elections to all adult men and a majority of adult women. Following the war, Britain became a permanent member of the Executive Council of the [League of Nations](/League_of_Nations) and was granted a [mandate](/League_of_Nations_mandate) over several former German and [Ottoman](/Ottoman_Empire) colonies. Under the leadership of [David Lloyd George](/David_Lloyd_George), the British Empire reached its greatest territorial extent, encompassing one-fifth of the globe's land surface and a quarter of its population.

By the mid-1920s, the [BBC](/BBC) had become a significant source of information and entertainment through its radio broadcasts. Experimental [television](/Television_in_the_United_Kingdom) broadcasts began in 1929, and the world's first scheduled BBC Television Service commenced in 1936. The rise of [Irish nationalism](/Irish_nationalism) and persistent disputes regarding the implementation of [Irish Home Rule](/Irish_Home_Rule) ultimately led to the [partition of the island](/Partition_of_Ireland) in 1921. This period was marked by conflict in what is now Northern Ireland from June 1920 to June 1922. The [Irish Free State](/Irish_Free_State) achieved independence, initially as a [Dominion](/Dominion) in 1922 and unequivocally in 1931 with the [Statute of Westminster 1931](/Statute_of_Westminster_1931). Northern Ireland, however, remained a part of the United Kingdom. The [1928 Equal Franchise Act](/1928_Equal_Franchise_Act) granted women electoral equality with men in national elections. Industrial unrest, evident in strikes during the mid-1920s, culminated in the [General Strike of 1926](/General_Strike_of_1926). Britain had not yet fully recovered from the economic impact of World War I when the [Great Depression](/Great_Depression_in_the_United_Kingdom) (1929–1932) inflicted widespread unemployment and hardship, particularly in traditional industrial regions, and fueled political and social unrest, with a surge in support for communist and socialist parties. A [coalition government](/National_Government_(1931)) was formed in 1931 to address these challenges.

Despite these economic difficulties, Britain was described as "a very wealthy country, formidable in arms, ruthless in pursuit of its interests and sitting at the heart of a global production system." Following [Nazi Germany](/Nazi_Germany)'s invasion of [Poland](/Invasion_of_Poland) in 1939, Britain entered [Second World War](/Second_World_War). Despite the swift defeat of its continental allies in the initial year of the conflict, Britain and its empire continued the war effort against Germany.

In 1940, the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force) achieved a critical victory over the German [Luftwaffe](/Luftwaffe) in the [Battle of Britain](/Battle_of_Britain), significantly averting a potential invasion. Urban centers endured extensive aerial bombardment during [the Blitz](/The_Blitz). The formation of the [Grand Alliance](/Grand_Alliance_(World_War_II)) in 1941, comprising Britain, the United States, and the [Soviet Union](/Soviet_Union), solidified the [Allies](/Allies_of_World_War_II) against the [Axis powers](/Axis_powers). Hard-fought victories were secured in the [Battle of the Atlantic](/Battle_of_the_Atlantic), the [North Africa campaign](/North_Africa_campaign), and the [Italian campaign](/Italian_campaign_(World_War_II)). British forces played a pivotal role in the [Normandy landings](/Normandy_landings) of 1944 and the subsequent [liberation of Europe](/Liberation_of_Europe). The British Army spearheaded the [Burma campaign](/Burma_campaign) against Japan, and the [British Pacific Fleet](/British_Pacific_Fleet) engaged the Japanese navy. Crucially, British scientists made vital contributions to the [Manhattan Project](/Manhattan_Project), the clandestine effort to develop the [nuclear weapon](/Nuclear_weapon).

#### Post-war 20th Century

The United Kingdom emerged as one of the [Big Three](/Big_Three_(World_War_II)) wartime powers, alongside the United States and the Soviet Union, participating in discussions to shape the [post-war world](/Aftermath_of_World_War_II). It was instrumental in drafting the [Declaration by United Nations](/Declaration_by_United_Nations) with the United States and secured a permanent seat on the [United Nations Security Council](/United_Nations_Security_Council). The UK also collaborated closely with the United States in establishing key international financial institutions such as the [International Monetary Fund](/International_Monetary_Fund), the [World Bank](/World_Bank), and the military alliance [NATO](/NATO). The war left the UK financially depleted and reliant on American aid through the [Marshall Plan](/Marshall_Plan), though it was spared the widespread devastation experienced by [eastern Europe](/Eastern_Europe).

In the immediate post-war period, the [Labour government](/Labour_Government_1945%E2%80%931951) under [Clement Attlee](/Clement_Attlee) implemented a comprehensive program of social reforms that profoundly impacted British society in the subsequent decades, contributing to the [Post-war consensus](/Post-war_consensus). Key industries and public utilities were [nationalised](/Nationalised), a comprehensive [welfare state](/Welfare_state) was established, and a universal, publicly funded healthcare system, the [National Health Service](/National_Health_Service), was created. The concurrent rise of nationalist movements in the colonies, coupled with the UK's diminished economic standing post-war, made a policy of [decolonisation](/Decolonisation) inevitable. India and Pakistan gained independence in 1947, and over the following three decades, the majority of former British colonies achieved sovereignty, many subsequently joining the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations).

The UK became the third nation to develop a [nuclear weapons arsenal](/Nuclear_weapons_and_the_United_Kingdom), conducting its first atomic bomb test, [Operation Hurricane](/Operation_Hurricane), in 1952. However, the limitations of Britain's post-war international role were starkly illustrated by the [Suez Crisis](/Suez_Crisis) in 1956. The global proliferation of the [English language](/English-speaking_world), its status as the [most-widely-spoken language](/List_of_languages_by_total_number_of_speakers) and third-most-spoken native language, ensured the continued international influence of [British literature](/British_literature) and [culture](/Culture_of_the_United_Kingdom). Addressing a labour shortage in the 1950s, the government encouraged [immigration](/Modern_immigration_to_the_United_Kingdom) from [Commonwealth countries](/Commonwealth_countries), leading to a more [multiracial](/Multiracialism) and [multicultural](/Multiculturalism) society in the following decades. Despite rising living standards in the late 1950s and 1960s, the UK's economic performance lagged behind that of key competitors like [West Germany](/West_Germany) and Japan. In 1969, the UK became the first democratic nation to lower its voting age to 18, through the [Representation of the People Act 1969](/Representation_of_the_People_Act_1969).

In the context of [European integration](/European_integration), the UK was a founding member of the [Western European Union](/Western_European_Union), established at the [London and Paris Conferences](/London_and_Paris_Conferences) in 1954. In 1960, it was among the seven founding members of the [European Free Trade Association](/European_Free_Trade_Association) (EFTA), but departed in 1973 to join the [European Communities](/European_Communities) (EC). A referendum in 1975 saw 67% of voters endorse continued membership. When the EC evolved into the [European Union](/European_Union) (EU) in 1992, the UK was one of its 12 founding member states.

From the late 1960s onwards, Northern Ireland experienced significant communal and [paramilitary](/Paramilitary) violence, a period known as [the Troubles](/The_Troubles), which occasionally extended to other parts of the UK. This period is generally considered to have concluded with the signing of the 1998 [Belfast "Good Friday" Agreement](/Belfast_Agreement). Following a protracted period of economic slowdown and industrial conflict in the 1970s, the [Conservative](/Conservative_Party_(UK)) government, led by [Margaret Thatcher](/Margaret_Thatcher) in the 1980s, implemented a radical agenda of [monetarism](/Monetarism), [deregulation](/Deregulation) (particularly in the financial sector, exemplified by the [Big Bang](/Big_Bang_(financial_markets)) in 1986), labor market reforms, and the privatization of state-owned enterprises.

HMS Invincible returns victorious after the [Falklands War](/Falklands_War) in 1982.

In 1982, [Argentina](/Argentina) invaded the British territories of [South Georgia](/South_Georgia_and_the_South_Sandwich_Islands) and the [Falkland Islands](/Falkland_Islands), precipitating the 10-week [Falklands War](/Falklands_War), which resulted in the defeat of Argentine forces. The inhabitants of the islands reaffirmed their strong preference for British sovereignty in a [2013 referendum](/2013_Falkland_Islands_sovereignty_referendum). From 1984, the British economy benefited from substantial revenues derived from [North Sea oil](/North_Sea_oil). Another British Overseas Territory, [Gibraltar](/Gibraltar), serves as a [key military base](/Port_of_Gibraltar); a [2002 referendum](/2002_Gibraltar_sovereignty_referendum) concerning shared sovereignty with Spain was overwhelmingly rejected by the Gibraltarians.

Towards the close of the 20th century, significant constitutional changes were enacted, leading to the establishment of [devolved](/Devolution) administrations for Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland. The [statutory incorporation](/Human_Rights_Act_1998) of human rights followed the acceptance of the [European Convention on Human Rights](/European_Convention_on_Human_Rights). The UK maintained its position as a [great power](/List_of_modern_great_powers), wielding considerable global diplomatic and military influence, and playing a leading role within the United Nations and [NATO](/NATO).

#### 21st Century

In the early 21st century, the UK broadly supported the United States' approach to the "[war on terror](/War_on_terror)". British troops participated in the [war in Afghanistan](/War_in_Afghanistan_(2001%E2%80%932021)), but the nation's [military deployment in Iraq](/Iraq_War) generated considerable controversy, leading to the [largest protest in British history](/15_February_2003_anti-war_protests) in opposition to the government led by [Tony Blair](/Tony_Blair).

The [Great Recession](/Great_Recession) (2007–2010) had a severe impact on the British economy, followed by a prolonged period of sluggish growth and stagnation. The [Cameron–Clegg coalition](/Cameron%E2%80%93Clegg_coalition) government, formed in 2010, implemented [austerity measures](/United_Kingdom_government_austerity_programme) aimed at reducing substantial public deficits. A referendum on [Scottish independence](/Scottish_independence) held in 2014 resulted in the Scottish electorate voting, by a margin of 55.3% to 44.7%, to remain part of the United Kingdom.

In 2016, 51.9% of voters in the UK participated in a referendum on [European Union](/European_Union) membership and voted to [leave the European Union](/2016_United_Kingdom_European_Union_membership_referendum) (EU). The [UK officially left the EU](/Brexit) on 31 January 2020. The [EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement](/EU%E2%80%93UK_Trade_and_Cooperation_Agreement), a free trade agreement between the UK and the EU, came into force on 1 May 2021.

The [COVID-19 pandemic](/COVID-19_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom) profoundly affected the British economy, caused significant [disruptions to education](/Impact_of_the_COVID-19_pandemic_on_education_in_the_United_Kingdom), and had [far-reaching societal and political consequences](/Social_impact_of_the_COVID-19_pandemic_in_the_United_Kingdom) throughout 2020 and 2021. The UK was the first country globally to administer an approved [COVID-19 vaccine](/COVID-19_vaccine), developing [its own vaccine](/Oxford%E2%80%93AstraZeneca_COVID-19_vaccine), which facilitated one of the world's fastest vaccine rollout programs.

***

### Geography

The United Kingdom's total land area is approximately 94,354 square miles (244,376 km²). It encompasses the majority of the [British Isles](/British_Isles), including the island of Great Britain, the northeastern portion of Ireland, and various smaller surrounding islands. Geographically, the UK is situated between the [North Atlantic Ocean](/North_Atlantic_Ocean) and the [North Sea]. Its southeastern coast is only 22 miles (35 km) from the coast of northern France, separated by the [English Channel](/English_Channel).

The proximity of the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man), [Jersey](/Jersey), and [Guernsey](/Guernsey) – all [Crown Dependencies](/Crown_Dependencies) – places them in union with the British monarch. However, they are not strictly part of the United Kingdom nor any of its constituent jurisdictions or countries. Their external affairs remain under the purview of the British government. The Isle of Man is located roughly midway between Great Britain and Ireland in the [Irish Sea](/Irish_Sea), while the Channel Islands are situated just off the northern coast of France.

The [Royal Greenwich Observatory](/Royal_Observatory,_Greenwich) in London holds historical significance as the site designated as the prime meridian at the [International Meridian Conference](/International_Meridian_Conference) in 1884, establishing the reference point for global time.

The UK spans latitudes [49°](/49th_parallel_north) to [61° N](/61st_parallel_north) and longitudes [9° W](/9th_meridian_west) to [2° E](/2nd_meridian_east). Northern Ireland shares a 310-mile (499 km) land border with the Republic of Ireland and possesses a coastline of 404 miles (650 km). The coastline of Great Britain, including its principal islands, stretches approximately 19,491 miles (31,368 km), with the main island of Great Britain accounting for 11,073 miles (17,820 km) of this total. Measuring coastlines is notoriously complex due to the [coastline paradox](/Coastline_paradox). The UK is connected to continental Europe via the [Channel Tunnel](/Channel_Tunnel), an engineering marvel that, at 31 miles (50 km) long (with 24 miles or 38 km underwater), holds the record for the longest underwater tunnel globally.

The UK is characterized by four distinct terrestrial [ecoregions](/Ecoregion): [Celtic broadleaf forests](/Celtic_broadleaf_forests), [English Lowlands beech forests](/English_Lowlands_beech_forests), [North Atlantic moist mixed forests](/North_Atlantic_moist_mixed_forests), and [Caledonian conifer forests](/Caledonian_Forest). As of 2023, the UK's woodland area was estimated at 3.25 million hectares, representing 13% of its total land area.

***

#### Climate

The United Kingdom predominantly experiences a temperate climate, characterized by generally cool temperatures and consistent rainfall throughout the year. Temperatures rarely fall below 0 °C (32 °F) or exceed 30 °C (86 °F). Some inland areas, particularly in upland regions of England, Wales, Northern Ireland, and most of Scotland, exhibit a [subpolar oceanic climate](/Subpolar_oceanic_climate). Higher elevations in Scotland can experience a [continental subarctic climate](/Subarctic_climate), and the highest mountain peaks are subject to [tundra climate](/Tundra_climate) conditions.

Prevailing winds typically blow from the southwest, bringing frequent spells of mild and wet weather originating from the Atlantic Ocean. However, eastern regions are largely shielded from these westerly influences, resulting in drier conditions. The warming effect of the [Gulf Stream](/Gulf_Stream) moderates winter temperatures, especially in the west, where winters are generally wetter, particularly at higher elevations. Summers tend to be warmest in southeastern England and coolest in the northern parts of the country. Heavy snowfall can occur in winter and early spring in mountainous areas, and occasionally settles to significant depths in lower-lying regions as well.

The average annual sunshine hours in the United Kingdom, based on the 1971–2000 period, stood at 1,339.7 hours, representing just under 30% of the maximum possible. Sunshine hours vary regionally, ranging from approximately 1,200 to 1,580 hours per year. Since 1996, the UK has generally experienced sunshine levels above the historical average.

Climate change poses significant challenges to the country. In 2023, a third of food price increases were attributed to its effects. In 2024, the United Kingdom ranked fifth out of 180 countries in the [Environmental Performance Index](/Environmental_Performance_Index). Legally, the UK has committed to achieving [net zero](/Net_zero) [greenhouse gas emissions](/Greenhouse_gas_emissions_by_the_United_Kingdom) by 2050.

***

#### Topography

[England](/Geography_of_England) constitutes 53% of the UK's landmass, covering 50,350 square miles (130,395 km²). The majority of England comprises lowland terrain, with upland and mountainous regions concentrated northwest of the [Tees–Exe line](/Tees%E2%80%93Exe_line), which broadly demarcates the country into [lowland and upland](/Lowland_and_upland) areas. Notable lowland regions include [Cornwall](/Cornwall), the [New Forest](/New_Forest), the [South Downs](/South_Downs), and the [Norfolk Broads](/The_Broads). Upland areas feature the [Lake District](/Lake_District), the [Pennines](/Pennines), the [Yorkshire Dales](/Yorkshire_Dales), [Exmoor](/Exmoor), and [Dartmoor](/Dartmoor). England's highest peak is [Scafell Pike](/Scafell_Pike) at 978 meters (3,209 ft) in the Lake District, and its largest island is the [Isle of Wight](/Isle_of_Wight).

[Scotland](/Geography_of_Scotland) accounts for 32% of the UK's total area, covering 30,410 square miles (78,772 km²). This region includes nearly 800 islands, notably the [Hebrides](/Hebrides), the [Orkney](/Orkney) Islands, and the [Shetland Islands](/Shetland_Islands). Scotland is the most mountainous of the UK's constituent countries. The [Highlands](/Scottish_Highlands) in the north and west represent a more rugged terrain, containing the majority of Scotland's mountainous land, including the [Cairngorms](/Cairngorms), [Loch Lomond and The Trossachs](/Loch_Lomond_and_The_Trossachs), and [Ben Nevis](/Ben_Nevis). Ben Nevis, at 1,345 meters (4,413 ft), is the highest point in the entire British Isles.

[Wales](/Geography_of_Wales) comprises less than 9% of the UK's land area, covering 8,020 square miles (20,779 km²). It is predominantly mountainous, although South Wales is generally less rugged than North and Mid Wales. The highest peaks in Wales are located in [Snowdonia](/Snowdonia), including [Snowdon](/Snowdon) (known in [Welsh](/Welsh_language) as Yr Wyddfa), which stands at 1,085 meters (3,560 ft) and is the highest mountain in Wales. Wales boasts a coastline of over 1,680 miles (2,704 km), encompassing the scenic [Pembrokeshire Coast](/Pembrokeshire_Coast). The largest island off the Welsh mainland is [Anglesey](/Anglesey) (Ynys Môn).

[Northern Ireland](/Geography_of_Ireland), separated from Great Britain by the [Irish Sea](/Irish_Sea) and the [North Channel](/North_Channel_(Great_Britain_and_Ireland)), covers an area of 5,470 square miles (14,160 km²) and is characterized by predominantly hilly terrain. It is home to [Lough Neagh](/Lough_Neagh), the largest lake in the British Isles by surface area (150 square miles or 388 km²), as well as [Lough Erne](/Lough_Erne), which features over 150 islands. The [Giant's Causeway](/Giant%27s_Causeway), a UNESCO [World Heritage Site](/World_Heritage_Site), is another notable geographical feature. The highest point in Northern Ireland is [Slieve Donard](/Slieve_Donard) in the [Mourne Mountains](/Mourne_Mountains), reaching 852 meters (2,795 ft).

***

### Politics

The UK operates as a [constitutional monarchy](/Constitutional_monarchy) and a [parliamentary democracy](/Parliamentary_democracy), functioning within the framework of the [Westminster system](/Westminster_system), often referred to as a "democratic parliamentary monarchy." It is fundamentally a [centralised](/Centralized_government), [unitary state](/Unitary_state), wherein the [Parliament of the United Kingdom](/Parliament_of_the_United_Kingdom) holds [sovereign](/Parliamentary_sovereignty_in_the_United_Kingdom) authority. Parliament comprises the elected [House of Commons](/House_of_Commons_of_the_United_Kingdom), the appointed [House of Lords](/House_of_Lords), and [the Crown](/The_Crown), personified by [the monarch](/Monarchy_of_the_United_Kingdom). While the primary legislative activities occur in the two houses, [royal assent](/Royal_assent) is constitutionally required for a bill to become an [act of Parliament](/Act_of_Parliament_(UK)), thereby entering the realm of [statute law](/Statute_law). The principle of parliamentary sovereignty means that the [British constitution](/Constitution_of_the_United_Kingdom) is [uncodified](/Uncodified_constitution), consisting of a diverse array of written sources, including parliamentary statutes, judicial case law, and international treaties, alongside established [constitutional conventions](/British_Constitution). Nonetheless, the [Supreme Court](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom) recognizes fundamental constitutional principles, such as parliamentary sovereignty, the [rule of law](/Rule_of_law), [democracy](/Democracy), and adherence to [international law](/Internationalism_(politics)).

[King Charles III](/Charles_III) serves as the [monarch](/Monarch) and [head of state](/Head_of_state) of the UK and 14 other independent [sovereign states](/Sovereign_state), collectively known as [Commonwealth realms](/Commonwealth_realm). The monarch formally embodies all executive authority through [the Crown](/The_Crown) and is described as "fundamental to the law and working of government in the UK." However, the exercise of these powers, including those under the [royal prerogative](/Royal_prerogative_in_the_United_Kingdom), is generally conducted on the [advice](/Advice_(constitutional_law)) of [ministers of the Crown](/Ministers_of_the_Crown) who are accountable to Parliament and, by extension, to the electorate. The monarch retains the right "to be consulted, the right to encourage, and the right to warn" in the performance of official duties. Furthermore, the monarch possesses [reserve powers](/Reserve_power) that can be deployed to uphold [responsible government](/Responsible_government) and avert [constitutional crises](/Constitutional_crisis).

For [general elections](/General_elections_in_the_United_Kingdom) to the House of Commons, the UK is divided into 650 [constituencies](/United_Kingdom_constituencies), each returning a single [member of Parliament](/Member_of_Parliament_(United_Kingdom)) (MP) elected via the [first-past-the-post](/First-past-the-post_voting) electoral system. MPs serve terms of up to five years, after which they must seek re-election. The [Conservative Party](/Conservative_Party_(UK)), colloquially known as the Tories, and the [Labour Party](/Labour_Party_(UK)) have been the dominant political forces since the 1920s, leading to the UK often being characterized as a [two-party system](/Two-party_system). Nevertheless, other [political parties](/List_of_political_parties_in_the_United_Kingdom) have secured seats in the House of Commons throughout this period, though none have achieved the dominance of the two main parties.

The [Palace of Westminster](/Palace_of_Westminster) in London serves as the seat of both houses of the Parliament of the United Kingdom.

The prime minister functions as the [head of government](/Head_of_government) in the UK. Operating under the direction and supervision of a [Cabinet](/Cabinet_of_the_United_Kingdom) composed of senior ministers selected and led by the prime minister, [His Majesty's Government](/His_Majesty%27s_Government) acts as the primary mechanism for public policy formulation, the administration of public services, and, through the [Privy Council](/Privy_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom), the promulgation of [statutory instruments](/Statutory_instrument_(UK)) and the tendering of advice to the monarch. Historically, prime ministers have concurrently held the position of [First Lord of the Treasury](/First_Lord_of_the_Treasury), a convention that has been consistently maintained since 1905. Furthermore, prime ministers have served as [Minister for the Civil Service](/Minister_for_the_Civil_Service) since 1968 and as [Minister for the Union](/Minister_for_the_Union) since 2019. Although appointed by the monarch, the prime minister is conventionally an MP, the leader of the political party commanding the most seats in the House of Commons, and maintains office by virtue of their ability to command the confidence of the House. As of 5 July 2024, the prime minister is [Sir Keir Starmer](/Keir_Starmer), the [leader of the Labour Party](/Leader_of_the_Labour_Party_(UK)).

While not integral parts of the United Kingdom, the three [Crown Dependencies](/Crown_Dependencies) – [Jersey](/Jersey), [Guernsey](/Guernsey), and the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man) – along with the 14 [British Overseas Territories](/British_Overseas_Territories), are subject to the sovereignty of the British Crown.

***

#### Administrative Divisions

The system of [counties](/Shire) or [shires](/Shire) originated in England and Scotland during the [early Middle Ages](/Early_Middle_Ages) and was extended throughout Great Britain and Ireland by the [early modern period](/Early_modern_period). The modern structure of [local government](/Local_government), based on elected councils and partially derived from ancient county boundaries, was established through separate parliamentary acts: in England and Wales [in 1888](/Local_Government_Act_1888), Scotland [in 1889](/Local_Government_(Scotland)_Act_1889), and Ireland [in 1898](/Local_Government_(Ireland)_Act_1898). This historical divergence means there is no uniform system of administrative or geographical demarcation across the UK, and each of [England and Wales](/English_law), [Scotland](/Scots_law), and [Northern Ireland](/Law_of_Northern_Ireland) maintains its own distinct legal jurisdictions. While these administrative arrangements remained relatively stable until the 19th century, they have undergone continuous evolution in terms of role and function.

The structure of [local government in England](/Local_government_in_England) is notably complex, with the distribution of responsibilities varying according to specific local arrangements. The upper-tier [subdivisions of England](/Subdivisions_of_England) are the nine [regions](/Regions_of_England), primarily utilized for statistical purposes. One of these regions, [Greater London](/Greater_London_Authority), has been governed by a directly elected assembly and mayor since 2000, following a positive outcome in a [1998 referendum](/1998_Greater_London_Authority_referendum).

[Local government in Scotland](/Local_government_in_Scotland) is organized into [32 council areas](/Subdivisions_of_Scotland), exhibiting considerable variation in size and population. The major cities – Glasgow, Edinburgh, Aberdeen, and Dundee – function as independent council areas, as does the [Highland Council](/Politics_of_the_Highland_council_area), which encompasses a third of Scotland's landmass but serves a population of just over 200,000. Each local council comprises elected councillors, numbering 1,223 in total.

[Local government in Wales](/Local_government_in_Wales) is structured into 22 [unitary authorities](/Unitary_authority), each led by a leader and cabinet elected by the council itself. These include the cities of Cardiff, [Swansea](/Swansea), and [Newport, Wales](/Newport,_Wales), which operate as unitary authorities. Elections for these bodies are conducted every four years using the first-past-the-post system.

[Local government in Northern Ireland](/Local_government_in_Northern_Ireland), since 1973, has been organized into 26 district councils, with members elected via the single transferable vote system. Their responsibilities are primarily limited to essential services such as waste collection, dog control, and the maintenance of parks and cemeteries. In 2008, proposals were approved to establish 11 new councils, intended to replace the existing system.

***

#### Devolution

The United Kingdom has undergone a process of devolution, transferring various powers from the UK Government to three of its constituent countries – Scotland, Northern Ireland, and Wales – as well as to regions within England. Since 1999, these areas have established their own governments and parliaments, responsible for a range of devolved matters. The extent of these devolved powers varies, with responsibilities assigned to the [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government), the [Welsh Government](/Welsh_Government), the [Northern Ireland Executive](/Northern_Ireland_Executive), and, in England, the [Greater London Authority](/Greater_London_Authority) and various [Combined Authorities](/Combined_authority). Among these devolved bodies, the [Scottish Parliament](/Scottish_Parliament) possesses the most extensive responsibilities for [devolved powers](/Devolved,_reserved_and_excepted_matters), and is widely recognized as "one of the most powerful devolved parliaments in the world."

The UK's [uncodified constitution](/Uncodified_constitution) means that constitutional matters are not among the powers that have been devolved. According to the doctrine of [parliamentary sovereignty](/Parliamentary_sovereignty_in_the_United_Kingdom), the UK Parliament theoretically retains the power to abolish the Scottish Parliament, the Senedd, or the Northern Ireland Assembly. However, legislation such as the [Scotland Act 2016](/Scotland_Act_2016) and the [Wales Act 2017](/Wales_Act_2017) explicitly states that the Scottish and Welsh Governments "are a permanent part of the United Kingdom's constitutional arrangements."

In practice, the abolition of devolution to the Scottish Parliament and the Senedd would face significant political obstacles, given that these institutions were established following referendums. The political constraints on the UK Parliament's ability to interfere with devolution in Northern Ireland are even more pronounced, as this arrangement is underpinned by an international agreement with the [Government of Ireland](/Government_of_Ireland). The UK Parliament has, through an act passed in 2020, imposed restrictions on the legislative powers of the three devolved parliaments concerning economic policy matters.

***

#### England

Unlike Scotland, Northern Ireland, and Wales, England does not possess a separate devolved government or national parliament. Instead, a process of devolving powers from the central government to local authorities has been implemented, commencing in 1998. The [Greater London Authority](/Greater_London_Authority) (GLA), colloquially known as City Hall, was established following a [referendum in 1998](/1998_Greater_London_Authority_referendum). It functions as the devolved regional government body for Greater London, comprising two branches: an [Executive Mayor](/Mayor_of_London) and the [London Assembly](/London_Assembly), which acts as a check and balance on the Mayor's authority.

A [Combined Authority](/Combined_Authority) (CA) represents a form of local government institution introduced in England outside of Greater London by the [Local Democracy, Economic Development and Construction Act 2009](/Local_Democracy,_Economic_Development_and_Construction_Act_2009). CAs enable groups of local authorities to pool responsibilities and receive devolved functions from central government to enhance the effectiveness of transport and economic policy delivery over broader geographical areas. A Combined County Authority (CCA) is a similar institution, established by the [Levelling-up and Regeneration Act 2023](/Levelling-up_and_Regeneration_Act_2023), exclusively for upper-tier authorities, such as [county councils](/County_council) and [unitary authorities](/Unitary_authority).

***

#### Scotland

Since 1999, Scotland has had a devolved national government and parliament with extensive powers over matters not explicitly [reserved](/Reserved_and_excepted_matters) for the UK Parliament. Scotland holds the most significant devolved powers among the UK's devolved parliaments, with comprehensive legislative control over areas such as [education](/Education_in_Scotland), [law and order](/Scots_law), [the economy](/Economy_of_Scotland), [healthcare](/Health_in_Scotland), [elections](/Elections_in_Scotland), [Crown Estate Scotland](/Crown_Estate_Scotland), the [planning system](/Planning_system_in_Scotland), and [housing](/Housing_in_Scotland).

Additional powers were transferred to the Scottish Parliament through the [Scotland Act 2012](/Scotland_Act_2012) and the [Scotland Act 2016](/Scotland_Act_2016). These include [some taxation powers](/Taxation_in_Scotland), encompassing full authority over [income tax](/Income_tax_in_Scotland) on employment income, [Land and Buildings Transaction Tax](/Land_and_Buildings_Transaction_Tax), [Landfill Tax](/Scottish_Landfill_Tax), Aggregates Levy, [Air Departure Tax](/Air_Departure_Tax), and [Revenue Scotland](/Revenue_Scotland). Furthermore, powers related to aspects of the [energy network](/Energy_in_Scotland), including [renewable energy](/Renewable_energy_in_Scotland), energy efficiency, and onshore [oil and gas licensing](/Oil_industry_in_Scotland), were also devolved. However, the economic autonomy of the Scottish Government is significantly constrained by a UK Parliament act passed in 2020, the [United Kingdom Internal Market Act 2020](/United_Kingdom_Internal_Market_Act_2020).

The [Scottish Government](/Scottish_Government) is currently a [Scottish National Party](/Scottish_National_Party) (SNP) [minority government](/Minority_government), led by the [first minister](/First_Minister_of_Scotland), [John Swinney](/John_Swinney), who also serves as the [leader of the SNP](/Leader_of_the_SNP). The [Scottish independence referendum](/2014_Scottish_independence_referendum) in 2014 resulted in a vote against independence, with 55.3% voting to remain within the United Kingdom. [Local government in Scotland](/Local_government_in_Scotland) is structured into [32 council areas](/Subdivisions_of_Scotland), varying widely in population and size. These councils are composed of 1,223 elected councillors.

The Scottish Parliament, distinct from the Scottish Government, consists of 129 elected [members of the Scottish Parliament](/Members_of_the_Scottish_Parliament) (MSPs). It functions as Scotland's legislative body, scrutinizing the work of the Scottish Government and deliberating on proposed legislation through parliamentary debates, committee reviews, and questioning.

***

#### Wales

Since 1999, Wales has possessed a devolved national government and legislature, known as the Senedd. Elections to the Senedd utilize the [additional member system](/Additional_member_system). The Senedd's powers are more circumscribed compared to those devolved to Scotland. The Senedd is empowered to legislate on any matter not explicitly reserved for the UK Parliament under the [Acts of Senedd Cymru](/Acts_of_Senedd_Cymru). The [Welsh Government](/Welsh_Government) is currently a [Welsh Labour](/Welsh_Labour) minority administration, led by the [first minister](/First_Minister_of_Wales), [Eluned Morgan](/Eluned_Morgan). [Local government in Wales](/Local_government_in_Wales) comprises 22 unitary authorities, each headed by a leader and cabinet elected by the council itself.

***

#### Northern Ireland

The devolved governance system in Northern Ireland is founded upon the 1998 [Good Friday Agreement](/Good_Friday_Agreement), which effectively concluded a three-decade period of communal conflict between [unionist](/Unionism_in_Ireland) and [nationalist](/Irish_nationalism) communities, known as [the Troubles](/The_Troubles). The Agreement, ratified by referendum, established [power-sharing](/Power_sharing) arrangements for a devolved government and legislature, referred to as the [Northern Ireland Executive](/Northern_Ireland_Executive) and the [Northern Ireland Assembly](/Northern_Ireland_Assembly), respectively. Elections to the Assembly employ the [single transferable vote](/Single_transferable_vote) system. The Executive and Assembly possess powers comparable to those devolved to Scotland. The Executive is jointly led by representatives designated as [unionist](/Designated_Unionist) and [nationalist](/Designated_Nationalist), serving as the [first minister and deputy first minister of Northern Ireland](/First_Minister_and_Deputy_First_Minister_of_Northern_Ireland), who jointly head the government. [Local government in Northern Ireland](/Local_government_in_Northern_Ireland), since 2015, has been structured into 11 councils with limited responsibilities.

***

#### Foreign Relations

The UK holds a permanent seat on the [United Nations Security Council](/United_Nations_Security_Council) and is a member of key international organizations including [NATO](/NATO), [AUKUS](/AUKUS), the [Commonwealth of Nations](/Commonwealth_of_Nations), the [G7](/G7), the [G20](/G-20_major_economies), the [OECD](/Organisation_for_Economic_Co-operation_and_Development), the [WTO](/World_Trade_Organization), the [Council of Europe](/Council_of_Europe), and the [OSCE](/Organization_for_Security_and_Co-operation_in_Europe). It maintains the [British Council](/British_Council), an organization operating in over 100 countries, dedicated to fostering international cultural and educational exchanges. The UK continues to be recognized as a [great power](/Great_power) with substantial political, cultural, economic, and military influence.

The UK is understood to share a "[Special Relationship](/Special_Relationship)" with the United States and maintains a close partnership with France, known as the "[Entente cordiale](/Entente_cordiale)". It collaborates on nuclear weapons technology with both nations. The [Anglo-Portuguese Alliance](/Anglo-Portuguese_Alliance) is considered the world's oldest existing treaty alliance. The UK also shares close ties with the Republic of Ireland, with both countries participating in a [Common Travel Area](/Common_Travel_Area) and cooperating through the [British-Irish Intergovernmental Conference](/British-Irish_Intergovernmental_Conference) and the [British-Irish Council](/British-Irish_Council). Britain's global reach and influence are further amplified by its extensive trading relationships, foreign investments, [official development assistance](/Official_development_assistance), and military engagements worldwide.

***

#### Law and Criminal Justice

The United Kingdom does not operate under a single, unified legal system. The [1706 Treaty of Union](/Treaty_of_Union) stipulated the continuation of Scotland's distinct legal system. Consequently, the UK comprises three separate [systems of law](/Legal_systems_of_the_world): English law, Northern Ireland law, and Scots law. A new [Supreme Court of the United Kingdom](/Supreme_Court_of_the_United_Kingdom) was established in October 2009, succeeding the [Appellate Committee of the House of Lords](/Judicial_functions_of_the_House_of_Lords) as the highest court of appeal. The [Judicial Committee of the Privy Council](/Judicial_Committee_of_the_Privy_Council), comprising the same members as the Supreme Court, serves as the ultimate court of appeal for several independent Commonwealth nations, the [British Overseas Territories](/British_Overseas_Territories), and the [Crown Dependencies](/Crown_Dependencies).

Both English law, applicable in England and Wales, and Northern Ireland law are rooted in [common law](/Common_law) (or [case law](/Case_law)) principles. This legal tradition originated in England during the [Middle Ages](/Middle_Ages) and has served as the foundation for numerous legal systems globally. The hierarchy of courts in England and Wales is headed by the [Senior Courts of England and Wales](/Senior_Courts_of_England_and_Wales), which includes the [Court of Appeal](/Court_of_Appeal_of_England_and_Wales), the [High Court of Justice](/High_Court_of_Justice) for civil matters, and the [Crown Court](/Crown_Court) for criminal proceedings. Scots law, conversely, operates as a hybrid system, drawing upon both common-law and [civil-law](/Civil_law_(legal_system)) principles. Its principal courts are the [Court of Session](/Court_of_Session) for civil cases and the [High Court of Justiciary](/High_Court_of_Justiciary) for criminal cases. The Supreme Court of the United Kingdom also functions as the highest court of appeal for civil cases governed by Scots law.

Crime statistics reveal an increase in England and Wales between 1981 and 1995. However, from its peak in 1995 to 2015, recorded crime saw an overall reduction of 66%, according to [UK crime statistics](/Crime_statistics_in_the_United_Kingdom). As of June 2023, the United Kingdom has the highest per-capita incarceration rate within Western Europe.

[UK labour laws](/United_Kingdom_labour_law) establish fundamental employment rights, including provisions for a [minimum wage](/National_Minimum_Wage_Act_1998), a minimum of 28 days of annual holiday, parental leave entitlements, statutory sick pay, and [pension](/Pensions_Act_2008) provisions. Same-sex marriage has been legally recognized in England, Scotland, and Wales since 2014, and in [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland) since 2020. [LGBT equality](/LGBT_rights_in_the_United_Kingdom) in the United Kingdom is generally considered to be advanced by contemporary international standards.

Following the UK's departure from the [EU](/European_Union), most disputes arising under UK-EU agreements are resolved through direct consultation between the parties. If consultations fail to yield a resolution, either party may initiate [arbitration](/Arbitration), typically overseen by the [Permanent Court of Arbitration](/Permanent_Court_of_Arbitration) (PCA) in [The Hague](/Peace_Palace). The [EU–UK Trade and Cooperation Agreement](/EU%E2%80%93UK_Trade_and_Cooperation_Agreement) mandates that the UK and EU cooperate and negotiate with "full mutual respect and good faith," as defined by international legal principles. Under the terms of the [Windsor Framework](/Windsor_Framework), matters pertaining to Northern Ireland that require the interpretation of EU law are referred to the [European Court of Justice](/European_Court_of_Justice) (ECJ), although the [Stormont Brake](/Stormont_Brake) mechanism allows for the potential prevention of new EU rules from taking effect.

***

#### Military

The British Armed Forces comprise three distinct professional branches: the [Royal Navy](/Royal_Navy) and [Royal Marines](/Royal_Marines), collectively forming the [Naval Service](/Naval_Service_(United_Kingdom)); the [British Army](/British_Army); and the [Royal Air Force](/Royal_Air_Force). The United Kingdom's armed forces are administered by the [Ministry of Defence](/Ministry_of_Defence_(United_Kingdom)) and overseen by the [Defence Council](/Defence_Council_of_the_United_Kingdom), chaired by the [Secretary of State for Defence](/Secretary_of_State_for_Defence). The [Commander-in-Chief](/Commander-in-Chief) of the armed forces is the [British monarch](/Monarchy_of_the_United_Kingdom), to whom all service members swear an oath of allegiance.

The armed forces are tasked with the responsibility of protecting the UK and its overseas territories, advancing the UK's global security interests, and supporting international peacekeeping initiatives. They actively participate in [NATO](/NATO) operations, including the [Allied Rapid Reaction Corps](/Allied_Rapid_Reaction_Corps), the [Five Power Defence Arrangements](/Five_Power_Defence_Arrangements), [RIMPAC](/RIMPAC), and various other global coalition efforts. The UK maintains [overseas garrisons](/Overseas_military_bases_of_the_United_Kingdom) and facilities in locations such as [Ascension Island](/RAF_Ascension_Island), [Bahrain](/Mina_Salman), [Belize](/Military_of_Belize), [Brunei](/Military_Forces_based_in_Brunei), [Canada](/British_Army_Training_Unit_Suffield), [Cyprus](/British_Forces_Cyprus), [Diego Garcia](/Diego_Garcia), the [Falkland Islands](/Military_of_the_Falkland_Islands), [Germany](/British_Forces_Germany), [Gibraltar](/British_Forces_Gibraltar), [Kenya](/British_Army_Training_Unit_Kenya), [Oman](/Oman), [Qatar](/Al_Udeid_Air_Base), and [Singapore](/Singapore).

According to data from the [Stockholm International Peace Research Institute](/Stockholm_International_Peace_Research_Institute) and the [International Institute for Strategic Studies](/International_Institute_for_Strategic_Studies), the UK's military expenditures ranked sixth or fifth globally in 2024. Defence spending constituted approximately 2.3% of the nation's [gross domestic product](/Gross_domestic_product) in that year. Following the conclusion of the [Cold War](/Cold_War), the UK's defence policy has been predicated on the assumption that "the most demanding operations" will be conducted as part of multinational coalitions.

***

#### Economy

The UK possesses a highly developed [social market economy](/Social_market_economy). With an estimated nominal GDP of £2.765 trillion in 2024, it ranks as the [sixth-largest national economy](/List_of_countries_by_GDP_(nominal)) worldwide and the [second-largest](/List_of_sovereign_states_in_Europe_by_GDP_(nominal)) in Europe. The [pound sterling](/Pound_sterling), its currency, is the [fourth-most-traded currency](/Foreign_exchange_market) in the global foreign exchange market and holds the position of the world's fourth-largest [reserve currency](/Reserve_currency), following the [United States dollar](/United_States_dollar), the [euro](/Euro), and the [yen](/Yen). The pound sterling maintains its substantial nominal value due to its historical stability and the absence of formal [redenomination](/Redenomination). As of 2025, the UK holds the position of the world's [fourth-largest exporter](/List_of_countries_by_exports) and [fourth-largest importer](/List_of_countries_by_imports) of goods and services. Despite exhibiting one of the highest levels of [income inequality](/Income_inequality_in_the_United_Kingdom) among [OECD](/OECD) member nations, the UK ranks very highly in the [Human Development Index](/Human_Development_Index), even when adjusted for inequality. The UK's [unemployment rate](/Unemployment_in_the_United_Kingdom) stood at 4.7% as of 2025, which is considered moderately low by European standards.

[HM Treasury](/HM_Treasury), under the leadership of the [Chancellor of the Exchequer](/Chancellor_of_the_Exchequer), is responsible for the formulation and implementation of the government's [public finance](/Public_finance) and [economic policy](/Economic_policy). The [Department for Business and Trade](/Department_for_Business_and_Trade) oversees matters related to business, international trade, and enterprise. The [Bank of England](/Bank_of_England) serves as the UK's [central bank](/Central_bank), responsible for the issuance of banknotes and coins denominated in pound sterling. Banks operating in Scotland and Northern Ireland retain the right to issue their own banknotes, provided they maintain adequate reserves of Bank of England notes to cover their circulation. The Bank of England is actively exploring the introduction of [a digital pound](/Central_bank_digital_currency) to facilitate instant settlement and enhance payment infrastructure.

***

#### Industries and Services

The [service sector](/Tertiary_sector_of_the_economy) accounted for approximately 80% of the UK's [GVA](/Gross_value_added) in 2023. As of that year, it was the world's [second-largest exporter of services](/List_of_countries_by_service_exports), and in 2024, it held the position of the world's largest net exporter of [financial services](/Financial_services_in_the_United_Kingdom). Between 2019 and 2023, the UK's service exports experienced a growth of 13%, surpassing its pre-pandemic and pre-Brexit peak. [London](/London) is recognized as the global capital for foreign exchange trading, commanding a market share of 38.1% in 2022 of the daily US$7.5 trillion global turnover. It stands as the largest urban economy in Europe and, alongside [New York](/New_York_City), is considered one of the cities most integrated into the [global economy](/World_economy). London also ranks as a leading international financial center, holding the second position in the 2025 [Global Financial Centres Index](/Global_Financial_Centres_Index). [Edinburgh](/Edinburgh), the UK's second-largest financial hub, ranks 29th globally in the same index.

The UK's [manufacturing sector](/Manufacturing_in_the_United_Kingdom) was the world's [10th-largest](/List_of_countries_by_manufacturing_output) and Europe's fourth-largest by value output in 2024. Due to sustained high domestic inflation, exacerbated by [COVID-19](/COVID-19_pandemic), elevated energy prices, and supply chain disruptions, the UK's import and export volumes for goods in 2023 were lower than in 2018. By the end of 2024, manufacturing accounted for 8% of the UK workforce and 8.6% of national economic output. In 2017, the [East Midlands](/East_Midlands_Manufacturing) and [West Midlands](/West_Midlands_Manufacturing) regions exhibited the highest proportions of employees in manufacturing, at 12.6% and 11.8% respectively. [London's manufacturing sector](/London_manufacturing) recorded the lowest figure at 2.8%.

The [country's tourism sector](/Tourism_in_the_United_Kingdom) is a vital contributor to the British economy, with London being named Europe's most popular destination in 2022. The [creative industries](/Creative_industries) accounted for 5.9% of the UK's GVA in 2019, demonstrating robust growth of 43.6% in real terms since 2010. In 2018, these industries contributed over £111 billion to the UK economy, with a growth rate more than five times that of the overall UK economy in that year. [Lloyd's of London](/Lloyd%27s_of_London), situated in London, is the world's largest market for [insurance](/Insurance) and [reinsurance](/Reinsurance). [WPP plc](/WPP_plc), one of the globe's leading advertising firms, is also headquartered in London. The UK represents a major retail market and the largest [e-commerce](/E-commerce) market in Europe. With consumer expenditures exceeding US$2 trillion in 2023, it boasts the [second-largest consumer market](/List_of_largest_consumer_markets) in Europe. [John Lewis](/John_Lewis_Partnership) stands as the UK's largest employee-owned business.

The [British automotive industry](/Automotive_industry_in_the_United_Kingdom) generates £47 billion in exports, representing 12% of the UK's total goods exports. In 2024, the UK produced 779,584 passenger vehicles and 125,649 commercial vehicles, with approximately 80% of domestically produced cars being exported. Britain is renowned for iconic car brands such as [Mini](/Mini_Hatch) and [Jaguar](/Jaguar_Cars), as well as luxury marques like [Rolls-Royce](/Rolls-Royce_Motor_Cars), [Bentley](/Bentley), and [Range Rover](/Range_Rover). The UK is a significant center for engine manufacturing, producing 1.59 million engines in 2024, and ranked as the world's [third-largest exporter of engines](/List_of_countries_by_engine_exports) in 2023. The [UK motorsport](/Motorsport_in_the_United_Kingdom) industry employs over 40,000 people, comprises around 4,300 companies, and generates an annual turnover of approximately £10 billion. Seven of the top ten [Formula One](/Formula_One) teams are based in the UK, leveraging their advanced technology in supercars and hypercars from manufacturers like [McLaren](/McLaren_Automotive), [Aston Martin](/Aston_Martin), and [Lotus](/Lotus_Cars). In 2024, the UK surpassed Germany to become Europe's largest market for [electric vehicles](/Electric_vehicles).

[Concorde](/Concorde), a supersonic airliner, significantly reduced transatlantic flight times from 8 hours to 3.5 hours. The [aerospace industry of the UK](/Aerospace_industry_in_the_United_Kingdom) ranks as the second-largest globally, with an annual turnover of approximately £30 billion. The [UK space industry](/British_space_programme) was valued at £17.5 billion in 2020/21, employing around 48,800 individuals. Since 2012, the number of space organizations has grown at an average annual rate of nearly 21%, reaching 1,293 organizations by 2021. The [UK Space Agency](/UK_Space_Agency) announced in 2023 an investment of £1.6 billion in space-related projects.

The [British agriculture industry](/Agriculture_in_the_United_Kingdom) is characterized by its intensity, high degree of mechanization, and efficiency relative to European standards. It meets approximately 60% of the nation's overall food requirements and 73% of its indigenous food needs, utilizing around 0.9% of the labor force (292,000 workers). Roughly two-thirds of agricultural production is dedicated to [livestock](/Livestock), with the remaining third focused on [arable crops](/Arable_crops). The UK retains a significant, albeit diminished, fishing industry, with at least 49% of UK fish sustainably caught in 2020. The estimated value of UK marine natural capital assets was £211 billion in 2021. The UK is endowed with abundant natural resources, including coal, [petroleum](/Petroleum), [natural gas](/Natural_gas), tin, limestone, iron ore, salt, clay, chalk, [gypsum](/Gypsum), lead, and silica, in addition to extensive arable land.

***

#### Science and Technology

England and Scotland were at the forefront of the [Scientific Revolution](/Scientific_Revolution) from the 17th century onwards. The United Kingdom spearheaded the [Industrial Revolution](/Industrial_Revolution) starting in the 18th century and has consistently produced scientists and [engineers](/List_of_British_engineers) credited with significant [advances](/List_of_British_innovations_and_discoveries). Notable theorists from the 17th and 18th centuries include [Isaac Newton](/Isaac_Newton), whose [laws of motion](/Newton%27s_laws_of_motion) and insights into [gravity](/Gravitation) are considered foundational to modern science. From the 19th century, [Charles Darwin](/Charles_Darwin) developed the theory of [evolution](/Evolution) by [natural selection](/Natural_selection), a cornerstone of modern biology, and [James Clerk Maxwell](/James_Clerk_Maxwell) formulated classical [electromagnetic theory](/Electromagnetic_theory). More recently, [Stephen Hawking](/Stephen_Hawking) made substantial contributions to the fields of [cosmology](/Cosmology), [quantum gravity](/Quantum_gravity), and the study of [black holes](/Black_holes).

The [Department for Science, Innovation and Technology](/Department_for_Science,_Innovation_and_Technology) (DSIT) is responsible for overseeing the development and management of the UK's scientific, research, and technological output. Scientific research and development remains a crucial focus within [British universities](/Universities_in_the_United_Kingdom), many of which have established [science parks](/Science_park) to foster industrial collaboration and innovation. In 2022, the UK produced 6.3% of the world's scientific research papers and accounted for 10.5% of scientific citations, ranking third globally in both metrics. The UK also holds the top position worldwide for Field-Weighted Citation Impact. Prominent scientific journals published in the UK include those from the [Royal Society](/Royal_Society), [Nature](/Nature_(journal)), the [British Medical Journal](/BMJ), and [The Lancet](/The_Lancet).

By 2024, the UK's technology sector had reached a valuation of US$1.2 trillion, surpassing the combined values of the French and German tech sectors. Cambridge University was recognized as the world's leading institution for nurturing successful technology founders. The [UK's artificial intelligence industry](/Artificial_intelligence_industry_in_the_United_Kingdom) is the largest in Europe by value, and the country ranked third globally in a 2024 report on artificial intelligence development by [Stanford University](/Stanford_University). The UK secured sixth place in the 2025 [Global Innovation Index](/Global_Innovation_Index). In 2025, the "[Tech Prosperity Deal](/Tech_Prosperity_Deal)" was announced, involving pledges of £150 billion in investment from US companies into the UK.

***

#### Transport

The UK maintains a comprehensive road network, totaling 29,145 miles (46,904 km) of main roads, 2,173 miles (3,497 km) of motorways, and 213,750 miles (344,000 km) of paved roads. The [M25 motorway](/M25_motorway), encircling London, is recognized as the world's largest and busiest bypass. In 2024, there were 41.7 million licensed vehicles in operation across the UK.

The UK possesses an extensive railway network spanning 10,072 miles (16,209 km). In Great Britain, the [British Rail](/British_Rail) network underwent privatization between 1994 and 1997, which was followed by a notable increase in passenger numbers. [Great British Railways](/Great_British_Railways) is a proposed state-owned public body tasked with overseeing [rail transport in Great Britain](/Rail_transport_in_Great_Britain). In the 2017 European Railway Performance Index, assessing intensity of use, quality of service, and safety, the UK ranked eighth among European national rail systems.

The UK offers a direct train service from London to [Paris](/Paris) via the [Eurostar](/Eurostar), which traverses the [Channel Tunnel](/Channel_Tunnel) beneath the [English Channel](/English_Channel). This tunnel, measuring 23.5 miles (37.8 km), is the longest undersea tunnel globally. A car transport service, [LeShuttle](/LeShuttle), also operates through the tunnel to France. The [Elizabeth line](/Elizabeth_line), a significant rail link connecting East and West London, was named in honor of [Queen Elizabeth II](/Queen_Elizabeth_II) in 2016 and opened in 2022. At the time of its completion, it was Europe's largest construction project and is estimated to contribute £42 billion to the UK economy. Another major infrastructure initiative is [High Speed 2](/High_Speed_2) (HS2), a high-speed railway project under construction since 2019, intended to connect London with [Birmingham](/Birmingham) and potentially extend further north, capable of speeds up to 225 mph.

In 2023, 4 billion bus journeys were undertaken in the UK, with 1.8 billion of these occurring within London. The iconic red [double-decker bus](/Double-decker_bus) has become an internationally recognized symbol of London and England, deeply embedded in popular culture. The [London bus network](/London_Buses) is exceptionally extensive, operating over 6,800 scheduled services daily, carrying approximately 6 million passengers across more than 700 distinct routes. This makes it one of the most comprehensive bus systems globally and the largest in Europe.

During 2024, British airports handled nearly 292.5 million passengers. The three busiest airports during this period were [London Heathrow Airport](/London_Heathrow_Airport) (83.9 million passengers), [Gatwick Airport](/Gatwick_Airport) (43.2 million passengers), and [Manchester Airport](/Manchester_Airport) (30.8 million passengers). London Heathrow Airport, situated 15 miles (24 km) west of the capital, ranks as the world's [second-busiest airport by international passenger traffic](/List_of_busiest_airports_by_passenger_traffic) and handles the highest volume of international passengers globally. It serves as the primary hub for the UK's flag carrier, [British Airways](/British_Airways), as well as [Virgin Atlantic](/Virgin_Atlantic). In 2023, 18.3 million passengers traveled internationally by rail and 18.1 million by sea.

***

#### Energy

In 2021, the UK ranked as the world's [14th-largest consumer and 22nd-largest producer of energy](/List_of_countries_by_energy_consumption_and_production). It is home to numerous major energy companies, including two of the six largest global oil and gas corporations: [BP](/BP) and [Shell](/Shell_plc).

Wind turbines overlooking [Ardrossan](/Ardrossan) in Scotland signify the UK's prominent role as a major producer of wind energy in Europe.

Renewable electricity sources accounted for 51% of the electricity generated in the UK in 2024. [Wind power](/Wind_power_in_the_United_Kingdom) emerged as the leading source, generating 30% of the UK's total electricity supply. The UK hosts the world's largest offshore wind farm, located off the coast of [Yorkshire](/Yorkshire).

As of 2023, the UK operated nine nuclear reactors, contributing approximately 15% of the nation's electricity. There are two reactors currently under construction, with plans for additional facilities. In the late 1990s, nuclear power plants supplied around 25% of the UK's annual electricity generation, but this proportion has gradually decreased as older plants have been decommissioned. The UK government is actively investing in [small modular reactors](/Small_modular_reactors) that operate via [nuclear fission](/Nuclear_fission) and is also supporting research and development into commercial [fusion reactors](/Fusion_reactors). To advance fusion technology, the government entered into a partnership with the United States in late 2023, setting a goal to achieve a "commercial grid-ready fusion reactor by 2040."

At the close of 2023, it was estimated that the UK possessed 1.1 billion barrels of oil equivalent in "proven" and "probable" [gas reserves](/Oil_and_gas_reserves_and_resource_quantification) and 2.3 billion barrels of oil equivalent in "proven" and "probable" [oil reserves](/North_Sea_oil) located offshore. These reserves contribute to reducing reliance on imports for energy security and support the transition towards renewable energy sources. According to the [UK's oil and gas regulator](/North_Sea_Transition_Authority), emissions from UK gas production are approximately four times lower than those associated with imported [liquefied natural gas](/Liquefied_natural_gas) (LNG).

In September 2024, the United Kingdom witnessed the closure of its final coal power station, effectively ceasing the use of [coal](/Coal) as a primary energy source. Despite substantial reserves, the UK currently does not engage in [fracking](/Fracking) (hydraulic fracturing) for [shale gas](/Shale_gas) due to prevailing environmental concerns.

***

#### Water Supply and Sanitation

Access to improved water supply and sanitation services is universal across the United Kingdom. It is estimated that 96% of households are connected to the public sewer network. According to data from the [Environment Agency](/Environment_Agency), total water abstraction for public water supply in the UK amounted to 16,406 megalitres per day in 2007.

In England and Wales, water and sewerage services are provided by 10 private regional water and sewerage companies, complemented by 13 predominantly smaller private "water-only" companies. In Scotland, these essential services are delivered by a single public entity, [Scottish Water](/Scottish_Water). Similarly, in Northern Ireland, services are provided by a sole public entity, [Northern Ireland Water](/Northern_Ireland_Water).

