#### Ethnicity

Historically, indigenous British populations are believed to be descended from groups that settled the islands prior to the 12th century, including the [Celts](/Celts), Romans, Anglo-Saxons, Norse, and Normans. [Welsh people](/Welsh_people) are considered potentially the oldest ethnic group within the UK. The UK has a history of non-white immigration, with [Liverpool](/Liverpool) hosting the oldest Black population in the country, dating back to at least the 1730s. Furthermore, Liverpool is home to Europe's oldest [Chinese](/British_Chinese) community, established in the 19th century.

In 2021, 83% of the UK population identified as White, meaning that 17% of the population identified with an [ethnic minority](/Minority_group) background. Ethnic diversity varies considerably across the UK. Regionally, in 2021, 46.2% of London's population identified as belonging to an ethnic minority, in contrast to Scotland, Wales, Northern Ireland, and the South West and North East regions of England, where this figure was less than 10%.

***

#### Language

The [English language](/English_language) serves as the [de facto](/De_facto) official and most widely spoken language throughout the United Kingdom. The UK actively promotes English globally to foster connections, understanding, and trust between its citizens and people in countries worldwide. Within the UK, the English language is spoken with distinctive characteristics that collectively constitute what is known as [British English](/British_English). The variety of dialects and accents is notable, with adjacent regions frequently exhibiting highly distinct variations. [Received Pronunciation](/Received_Pronunciation) is traditionally associated with educated speakers in southern England. The primary national dialects include [Scottish English](/Scottish_English), [Welsh English](/Welsh_English), and [Northern Irish English](/Northern_Irish_English). Distinct regional varieties encompass [Brummie](/Brummie_dialect), [Cockney](/Cockney), [Geordie](/Geordie), [Mancunian](/Manchester_dialect), [Scouse](/Scouse), [West Country](/West_Country_English), [Yorkshire](/Yorkshire_dialect), and [MLE](/Multicultural_London_English) (Multicultural London English).

Three indigenous [Celtic languages](/Celtic_languages) are spoken in the UK: [Welsh](/Welsh_language), [Irish](/Irish_language), and [Scottish Gaelic](/Scottish_Gaelic). [Cornish](/Cornish_language), which ceased to be a first language by the late 18th century, is currently undergoing a revival, with a small number of second-language speakers. In the [2021 census](/2021_United_Kingdom_census), the [Welsh-speaking population](/Welsh-speaking_population) of Wales, aged three and above, was recorded at 538,300 (17.8%). Additionally, it is estimated that approximately 200,000 Welsh speakers reside in England. In the 2021 census for Northern Ireland, 12.4% of individuals reported some ability in the [Irish language](/Irish_language_in_Northern_Ireland), and 10.4% demonstrated proficiency in the [Ulster-Scots](/Ulster_Scots_dialects) language.

In 2001, over 92,000 people in Scotland, representing just under 2% of the population, possessed some level of Gaelic language ability, with 72% of those living in the [Outer Hebrides](/Outer_Hebrides) being fluent. The number of children receiving instruction in either Welsh or Scottish Gaelic is on the rise. [Scots](/Scots_language), a language descended from early northern [Middle English](/Middle_English), holds limited [recognition](/European_Charter_for_Regional_or_Minority_Languages) alongside its regional variant, [Ulster Scots](/Ulster_Scots_dialects) in Northern Ireland, without specific commitments to its protection and promotion. As of April 2020, there are approximately 151,000 users of [British Sign Language](/British_Sign_Language) (BSL), a [sign language](/Sign_language) utilized by deaf individuals, within the UK.

In 2013, it was estimated that 95% of the UK's population were monolingual English speakers. In the same year, over 5% of the population were estimated to speak languages introduced to the UK through immigration. [South Asian languages](/South_Asian_languages) constitute the largest group, including [Punjabi](/Punjabi_language), [Urdu](/Urdu), [Bengali](/Bengali_language), [Sylheti](/Sylheti_language), [Hindi](/Hindi), [Pahari-Pothwari](/Pahari-Pothwari), [Tamil](/Tamil_language), and [Gujarati](/Gujarati_language). In the 2011 census, [Polish](/Polish_language) was the second most spoken language in England, with 546,000 speakers. In 2019, approximately three-quarters of a million people reported speaking little or no English.

***

#### Religion

[Christianity](/Christianity) has been the dominant religious influence in the United Kingdom for over 1,400 years. Although a majority of citizens continue to identify with Christianity in surveys, regular church attendance has significantly declined since the mid-20th century. Concurrently, immigration and demographic shifts have contributed to the growth of Islam and other faiths. This trend has led some observers to characterize the UK as a multi-faith, [secularised](/Secularised), or [post-Christian](/Post-Christian) society.

In the 2021 census, 46.5% of respondents identified as Christian, with the next largest religious affiliations being [Islam](/Islam_in_the_United_Kingdom) (5.9%), [Hinduism](/Hinduism_in_the_United_Kingdom) (1.6%), [Sikhism](/Sikhism_in_the_United_Kingdom) (0.8%), [Buddhism](/Buddhism_in_the_United_Kingdom) (0.4%), and [Judaism](/Judaism_in_the_United_Kingdom) (0.4%). A further 0.6% identified with other religions, while 38% stated they had [no religion](/Irreligion_in_the_United_Kingdom) and 6% reported no religious preference. A 2007 survey by [Tearfund](/Tearfund) indicated that one in ten Britons attended church weekly. Between the 2001 and 2011 censuses, there was a 12% decrease in individuals identifying as Christian, while the percentage reporting no religious affiliation doubled. This contrasted with growth in other major religious categories, with the number of [Muslims](/Muslims) increasing the most, reaching approximately 5% of the population. The Muslim population grew from 1.6 million in 2001 to 2.7 million in 2011, establishing it as the second-largest religious group in the UK.

The [Church of England](/Church_of_England) holds the status of the [established church](/State_religion). It maintains [representation](/Lords_Spiritual) within the UK Parliament, and the British monarch serves as its [Supreme Governor](/Supreme_Governor_of_the_Church_of_England). In [Scotland](/Religion_in_Scotland), the [Church of Scotland](/Church_of_Scotland) is recognized as the [national church](/National_church). It operates independently of state control, and the British monarch is an ordinary member, obligated by oath to "maintain and preserve the Protestant Religion and [Presbyterian Church Government](/Presbyterian_polity)" upon accession. The [Church in Wales](/Church_in_Wales) was disestablished in 1920. Following the disestablishment of the [Church of Ireland](/Church_of_Ireland) in 1870, prior to the [partition of Ireland](/Partition_of_Ireland), there is no established church in Northern Ireland. Although the 2001 census did not collect UK-wide data on adherence to specific Christian denominations, estimates suggest that 62% of Christians are Anglican, 13.5% are Catholic, 6% are Presbyterian, and 3.4% are Methodist, with smaller numbers belonging to other denominations.

***

#### Migration

Immigration is a contributing factor to the UK's rising population, with arrivals and their UK-born children accounting for approximately half of the population increase between 1991 and 2001. Statistics released in 2015 indicated that 27% of live births in the UK in 2014 were to mothers born outside the UK.

In 2013, approximately 208,000 foreign nationals were naturalized as British citizens, marking the highest number since 1962. This figure decreased to around 125,800 in 2014. Between 2009 and 2013, the average annual number of British citizenships granted was 195,800. The primary countries of origin for those naturalized in 2024 included Pakistan, India, [Nigeria](/Nigeria), the [Philippines](/Philippines), [Bangladesh](/Bangladesh), Italy, Romania, and Iran. The number of settlement grants, which confer [permanent residency](/Permanent_residency) in the UK but not citizenship, was approximately 154,700 in 2013, an increase from the preceding two years. Long-term net migration—the difference between immigration and emigration—reached a record high of 860,000 in 2023, with immigration at 1.326 million and emigration at 466,000. In comparison, net migration in 2024 was estimated at 431,000, with immigration at 948,000 and emigration at 517,000.

[Emigration](/British_diaspora) played a significant role in British society during the 19th century. Between 1815 and 1930, an estimated 11.4 million people emigrated from Britain and 7.3 million from Ireland. By the end of the 20th century, it is estimated that around 300 million individuals of British and Irish descent had established permanent settlements globally. In 2006, at least 5.5 million UK-born individuals resided abroad, primarily in Australia, Spain, the United States, and Canada.

***

#### Education

Education in the United Kingdom is a [devolved](/Devolution) matter, with each constituent country maintaining its own distinct education system. Approximately 38% of the UK population holds a university or [college degree](/College_degree), representing the highest percentage in Europe and one of the highest globally. The UK is home to numerous universities, including the [University of Oxford](/University_of_Oxford) and [University of Cambridge](/University_of_Cambridge), which consistently rank among the world's leading institutions.

University education is subject to varying [tuition fees](/Student_loans_and_grants_in_the_United_Kingdom) across different regions of the UK. England and Wales have a fixed maximum annual fee for all UK citizens, contingent upon achieving a certain income level. Repayment of this fee is typically managed through [general taxation](/Taxation_in_the_United_Kingdom). Northern Ireland and Scotland offer reduced maximum fees or no fees for citizens from those respective regions. Certain NHS courses provide bursaries that cover tuition fees, and it was noted in 2017 that each medical student receives a subsidy of £230,000 throughout their training.

In 2022, the [Programme for International Student Assessment](/Programme_for_International_Student_Assessment) (PISA), coordinated by the [OECD](/OECD), ranked the overall knowledge and skills of British 15-year-olds as 14th in the world across reading, mathematics, and science. The average British student scored 494, exceeding the OECD average of 478.

***

#### Healthcare

The modern system of [universal](/Universal_service) [publicly funded healthcare](/Publicly_funded_health_care) in the United Kingdom traces its origins to the establishment of the [National Health Service](/National_Health_Service) (NHS) in 1949. The NHS is the primary healthcare provider across the UK. The widespread public appreciation for the NHS has led to its description as a "national religion." Healthcare in the United Kingdom is a [devolved matter](/Devolution), with each constituent country operating its own system of universal, publicly funded healthcare. Private healthcare options are also available. Public healthcare is provided to all [UK permanent residents](/British_nationality_law) and is largely free at the point of need, funded through [general taxation](/Taxation_in_the_United_Kingdom). In 2000, the [World Health Organization](/World_Health_Organization) ranked the UK's healthcare provision as eighteenth best globally and fifteenth best in Europe.

Healthcare expenditure has seen a significant increase since 1979. According to 2018 [OECD](/OECD) data, which includes social care expenditure within its health calculations, the UK spent £3,121 per person on healthcare. In 2017, the UK's healthcare spending was £2,989 per person, positioning it near the median expenditure among OECD member states.

Regulatory bodies operate on a UK-wide basis, such as the [General Medical Council](/General_Medical_Council), the [Nursing and Midwifery Council](/Nursing_and_Midwifery_Council), and various non-governmental [Royal Colleges](/Medical_royal_college). Political and operational responsibility for healthcare delivery rests with four national [executives](/Executive_(government)). Healthcare in England falls under the purview of the UK Government, while healthcare in Northern Ireland is managed by the Northern Ireland Executive. Healthcare in Scotland is the responsibility of the Scottish Government, and in Wales, it is overseen by the Welsh Government. Each National Health Service operates with distinct policies and priorities.

***

#### Culture

The cultural landscape of the United Kingdom is shaped by its island geography, its extensive history, and its constitution as a [political union](/Political_union) of four countries, each preserving unique traditions, customs, and symbolism. British influence is evident in the language, culture, and [legal systems](/Common_law) of many of [its former colonies](/List_of_countries_that_have_gained_independence_from_the_United_Kingdom), notably the United States, Australia, Canada, New Zealand, and Ireland, forming a shared cultural sphere often referred to as the [Anglosphere](/Anglosphere). The UK's [soft power influence](/Anglicisation) has led to its characterization as a [cultural superpower](/Cultural_superpower). A global survey conducted in 2024 ranked the UK third in the 'Most Influential Countries' rankings, following the US and China.

***

##### Literature

British literature encompasses works associated with the United Kingdom, the [Isle of Man](/Isle_of_Man), and the [Channel Islands](/Channel_Islands). The predominant language of British literature is English. In 2022, the UK achieved a record sale of 669 million physical books. Britain is renowned for its contributions to [children's literature](/Literature_for_children), with authors such as [Daniel Defoe](/Daniel_Defoe), [Rudyard Kipling](/Rudyard_Kipling), [Lewis Carroll](/Lewis_Carroll), and [Beatrix Potter](/Beatrix_Potter) (also an illustrator of her own works). Other notable figures include [A. A. Milne](/A._A._Milne), [Enid Blyton](/Enid_Blyton), [J. R. R. Tolkien](/J._R._R._Tolkien), [Roald Dahl](/Roald_Dahl), [Terry Pratchett](/Terry_Pratchett), and [J. K. Rowling](/J._K._Rowling), author of the [Harry Potter](/Harry_Potter) series, which stands as the [best-selling book series](/List_of_best-selling_book_series) of all time.

The playwright and poet [William Shakespeare](/William_Shakespeare) is widely regarded as the greatest dramatist in history and is celebrated as the [national poet](/National_poet) of England. Other significant figures in English literature include [Geoffrey Chaucer](/Geoffrey_Chaucer), known for [The Canterbury Tales](/The_Canterbury_Tales); the poet [William Wordsworth](/William_Wordsworth) and other [Romantic poets](/Romantic_Poetry); and novelists such as [Charles Dickens](/Charles_Dickens), [H. G. Wells](/H._G._Wells), [George Orwell](/George_Orwell), [Aldous Huxley](/Aldous_Huxley), and [Ian Fleming](/Ian_Fleming). The 20th-century English crime writer [Agatha Christie](/Agatha_Christie) holds the distinction of being the [best-selling novelist](/List_of_best-selling_fiction_authors) in history. A BBC poll of global critics identified twelve of the top 25 novels by British authors as works by women, including contributions from [George Eliot](/George_Eliot), [Virginia Woolf](/Virginia_Woolf), [Charlotte Brontë](/Charlotte_Brontë), [Emily Brontë](/Emily_Brontë), [Mary Shelley](/Mary_Shelley), [Jane Austen](/Jane_Austen), [Doris Lessing](/Doris_Lessing), and [Zadie Smith](/Zadie_Smith).

Scottish literature features prominent authors such as [Arthur Conan Doyle](/Arthur_Conan_Doyle), creator of [Sherlock Holmes](/Sherlock_Holmes); [Sir Walter Scott](/Walter_Scott); [J. M. Barrie](/J._M._Barrie); [Robert Louis Stevenson](/Robert_Louis_ Stevenson), whose novel [Treasure Island](/Treasure_Island) significantly influenced the depiction of [pirates in the arts and popular culture](/Pirates_in_the_arts_and_popular_culture); and the poet [Robert Burns](/Robert_Burns), considered the national poet of Scotland. More recent contributions include the works of [Hugh MacDiarmid](/Hugh_MacDiarmid) and [Neil M. Gunn](/Neil_M._Gunn) during the [Scottish Renaissance](/Scottish_Renaissance), alongside grimmer narratives by [Ian Rankin](/Ian_Rankin) and [Iain Banks](/Iain_Banks). Edinburgh holds the distinction of being UNESCO's first designated worldwide [City of Literature](/City_of_Literature).

Welsh literature includes [Y Gododdin](/Y_Gododdin), considered Britain's oldest known poem, likely composed in the late 6th century. Written in [Cumbric](/Cumbric_language) or [Old Welsh](/Old_Welsh), it contains the earliest recorded reference to [King Arthur](/King_Arthur). The [Arthurian legend](/Arthurian_legend) was further developed by [Geoffrey of Monmouth](/Geoffrey_of_Monmouth). [Dafydd ap Gwilym](/Dafydd_ap_Gwilym) (fl. 1320–1370) is widely acknowledged as one of the preeminent European poets of his era. [Daniel Owen](/Daniel_Owen) is credited with authoring the first Welsh-language novel, publishing [Rhys Lewis](/Rhys_Lewis_(novel)) in 1885. Among the most celebrated [Anglo-Welsh poets](/Anglo-Welsh_poetry) are [Dylan Thomas](/Dylan_Thomas) and [R. S. Thomas](/R._S._Thomas), the latter having been nominated for the [Nobel Prize in Literature](/Nobel_Prize_in_Literature) in 1996. Leading Welsh novelists of the 20th century include [Richard Llewellyn](/Richard_Llewellyn) and [Kate Roberts](/Kate_Roberts_(author)).

Northern Ireland's most distinguished writer is [C. S. Lewis](/C._S._Lewis), a Belfast native renowned for [The Chronicles of Narnia](/The_Chronicles_of_Narnia). Irish writers active during periods when all of Ireland was part of the United Kingdom include [Oscar Wilde](/Oscar_Wilde), [Bram Stoker](/Bram_Stoker) (author of [Dracula](/Dracula)), and [George Bernard Shaw](/George_Bernard_Shaw). Numerous authors originating from outside the United Kingdom also relocated to the UK, including [Joseph Conrad](/Joseph_Conrad), [T. S. Eliot](/T._S._Eliot), [Kazuo Ishiguro](/Kazuo_Ishiguro), Sir [Salman Rushdie](/Salman_Rushdie), and [Ezra Pound](/Ezra_Pound).

***

#### Philosophy

The United Kingdom is celebrated for "[British Empiricism](/British_Empiricism)," a philosophical school asserting that knowledge is validated solely through experience. It is also noted for "[Scottish Philosophy]," sometimes referred to as the '[Scottish School of Common Sense](/Scottish_School_of_Common_Sense)'. The most prominent philosophers associated with British Empiricism are [John Locke](/John_Locke), [George Berkeley](/George_Berkeley), and [David Hume](/David_Hume). Major proponents of the Scottish "common sense" school include [Dugald Stewart](/Dugald_Stewart), [Thomas Reid](/Thomas_Reid), and [William Hamilton](/Sir_William_Hamilton,_9th_Baronet). Two British figures, [Jeremy Bentham](/Jeremy_Bentham) and [John Stuart Mill](/John_Stuart_Mill), are particularly recognized for their contributions to the ethical theory of [utilitarianism](/Utilitarianism), notably Mill's seminal work [Utilitarianism](/Utilitarianism_(book)).

***

#### Music

A diverse array of musical styles has achieved popularity in the UK, including the [folk music](/Folk_music) traditions of [England](/Folk_music_of_England), [Scotland](/Folk_music_of_Scotland), [Wales](/Music_of_Wales), and [Northern Ireland](/Folk_music_of_Northern_Ireland). English folk music often features melodic ballads with strong lyrical content and instrumental music for country dancing, typically utilizing the accordion and fiddle. Scottish folk music is characterized by bagpipes and fiddles playing traditional dance tunes with lively tempos. Welsh folk music incorporates harps and vocal harmonies, frequently sung in the Welsh language. Northern Irish folk blends fiddle and flute traditions, drawing from both Scottish and Irish influences.

Historically, the UK boasts a rich tradition of [Renaissance music](/Renaissance_music) from the [Tudor period](/Tudor_period), with works such as [masses](/Mass_(music)), [madrigals](/Madrigal), and [lute](/Lute) compositions by [Thomas Tallis](/Thomas_Tallis), [John Taverner](/John_Taverner), [William Byrd](/William_Byrd), [Orlando Gibbons](/Orlando_Gibbons), and [John Dowland](/John_Dowland). Following the [Stuart Restoration](/Stuart_Restoration), an English tradition of dramatic [masques](/Masque), anthems, and airs emerged, spearheaded by [Henry Purcell](/Henry_Purcell), and subsequently by [Thomas Arne](/Thomas_Arne) and others. [George Frideric Handel](/George_Frideric_Handel) composed the anthem [Zadok the Priest](/Zadok_the_Priest) for the [coronation of George II](/Coronation_of_George_II), which became the traditional ceremonial music for the anointing of subsequent monarchs. Handel's extensive repertoire of oratorios, including his renowned [Messiah](/Messiah_(Handel)), were composed in English.

In the latter half of the 19th century, [Arthur Sullivan](/Arthur_Sullivan), in collaboration with his librettist [W. S. Gilbert](/W._S._Gilbert), produced their highly popular [Savoy operas](/Savoy_opera). [Edward Elgar](/Edward_Elgar) composed a diverse range of musical works. Composers increasingly drew inspiration from the English countryside and its [folk music](/Folk_music), notably [Gustav Holst](/Gustav_Holst), [Ralph Vaughan Williams](/Ralph_Vaughan_Williams), and [Benjamin Britten](/Benjamin_Britten), a pioneer of modern British opera. Among the prominent post-war composers, several have forged distinct musical identities: [Peter Maxwell Davies](/Peter_Maxwell_Davies) (associated with Orkney), [Harrison Birtwistle] (associated with mythological themes), and [John Tavener](/John_Tavener) (associated with religious music). Contemporary classical singers include [Alfie Boe](/Alfie_Boe), [Bryn Terfel](/Bryn_Terfel), [Katherine Jenkins](/Katherine_Jenkins), [Michael Ball](/Michael_Ball), [Roderick Williams](/Roderick_Williams), [Russell Watson](/Russell_Watson), and [Sarah Brightman](/Sarah_Brightman), while violinists like [Nicola Benedetti](/Nicola_Benedetti) and [Nigel Kennedy](/Nigel_Kennedy) have achieved considerable renown.

According to [The New Grove Dictionary of Music and Musicians](/The_New_Grove_Dictionary_of_Music_and_Musicians), the term "[pop music](/Pop_music)" originated in Britain in the mid-1950s, describing the fusion of [rock and roll](/Rock_and_roll) with "new youth music." The Oxford Dictionary of Music notes that artists such as [the Beatles](/The_Beatles) and [the Rolling Stones](/The_Rolling_Stones) propelled pop music to the forefront of popular culture in the early 1960s. Birmingham gained recognition as the birthplace of [heavy metal](/Heavy_metal_music), with the band [Black Sabbath](/Black_Sabbath) forming there in the 1960s. In subsequent decades, Britain contributed significantly to the evolution of [rock music](/Rock_music), with British acts pioneering genres such as [hard rock](/Hard_rock), [raga rock](/Raga_rock), heavy metal, [space rock](/Space_rock), [glam rock](/Glam_rock), [Gothic rock](/Gothic_rock), [psychedelic rock](/Psychedelic_rock), and [punk rock](/Punk_rock). British artists also played a key role in developing [neo soul](/Neo_soul) and creating [dubstep](/Dubstep). Contemporary UK artists are prominent figures in English-speaking [rap music](/Rappers), alongside their American counterparts, including [Stormzy](/Stormzy), [Kano](/Kano_(rapper)), [Yxng Bane](/Yxng_Bane), [Ramz](/Ramz_(rapper)), [Little Simz](/Little_Simz), and [Skepta](/Skepta).

The British-born singer [Rod Stewart](/Rod_Stewart) is among the [best-selling music artists](/List_of_best-selling_music_artists) globally. The Beatles, with worldwide sales exceeding 1 billion units, are the [biggest-selling band](/List_of_best-selling_music_artists) and are widely regarded as the [most influential band in the history of popular music](/Cultural_impact_of_the_Beatles). Other prominent British contributors to popular music over the past 50 years include the Rolling Stones, [Pink Floyd](/Pink_Floyd), [Queen](/Queen_(band)), [Led Zeppelin](/Led_Zeppelin), the [Bee Gees](/Bee_Gees), and [Elton John](/Elton_John), all of whom have achieved global record sales of 200 million or more. The [Brit Awards](/Brit_Awards) are the annual music awards presented by the [BPI](/British_Phonographic_Industry), with recipients of the [Outstanding Contribution to Music](/Brit_Award_for_Outstanding_Contribution_to_Music) award including The Who, [David Bowie](/David_Bowie), [Eric Clapton](/Eric_Clapton), [Rod Stewart](/Rod_Stewart), [The Police](/The_Police), and Fleetwood Mac (a British-American band). More recent UK music acts achieving international success include [George Michael](/George_Michael), [Oasis](/Oasis_(band)), [Spice Girls](/Spice_Girls), [Radiohead](/Radiohead), [Coldplay](/Coldplay), [Arctic Monkeys](/Arctic_Monkeys), [Robbie Williams](/Robbie_Williams), [Amy Winehouse](/Amy_Winehouse), [Susan Boyle](/Susan_Boyle), [Adele](/Adele), [Ed Sheeran](/Ed_Sheeran), [Lewis Capaldi](/Lewis_Capaldi), [One Direction](/One_Direction), [Harry Styles](/Harry_Styles), and [Dua Lipa](/Dua_Lipa).

Many British cities are recognized for their musical contributions. Artists from Liverpool have produced 54 UK chart number 1 hit singles, achieving the highest per capita rate globally. Glasgow's musical significance was acknowledged in 2008 when UNESCO designated it a [City of Music](/City_of_Music_(UNESCO)). Manchester played a pivotal role in the popularization of dance music genres such as [acid house](/Acid_house) and, from the mid-1990s, [Britpop](/Britpop). London and Bristol are closely associated with the origins of electronic music sub-genres like [drum and bass](/Drum_and_bass) and [trip hop](/Trip_hop).

UK dance music traces its roots to [Sound System Culture](/Sound_system_(Jamaican)) within the Black British community and the [New Age Traveller](/New_Age_travellers) movement of the 1960s and 1970s. It also draws influence from the [Chicago House](/House_music) and [Detroit Techno](/Detroit_techno) scenes. In the late 1980s, dance music experienced an explosion with the rise of [Rave](/Rave) culture, primarily centered around [Acid House](/Acid_House) tracks. Novelty records, such as Smart E's [Sesame's Treet](/Sesame%27s_Treet) and The Prodigy's [Charly](/Charly_(song)), contributed to its mainstream appeal, alongside the [Balearic sound](/Balearic_beat) brought back from Ibiza's club scene. This evolution paved the way for genres like [UK Garage](/UK_Garage), [Speed Garage](/Speed_Garage), [Drum and bass](/Drum_and_bass), [Jungle](/Jungle_music), [Trance](/Trance_music), and [Dubstep](/Dubstep). Influential UK dance acts, both past and present, include [808 State](/808_State), [Orbital](/Orbital_(band)), [The Prodigy](/The_Prodigy), [Underworld](/Underworld_(band)), [Roni Size](/Roni_Size), [Leftfield](/Leftfield), [Massive Attack](/Massive_Attack), [Groove Armada](/Groove_Armada), [Fatboy Slim](/Fatboy_Slim), [Faithless](/Faithless), [Basement Jaxx](/Basement_Jaxx), [Chemical Brothers](/Chemical_Brothers), [Sub Focus](/Sub_Focus), [Chase & Status](/Chase_%26_Status), [Disclosure](/Disclosure_(band)), [Calvin Harris](/Calvin_Harris), and [Fred Again](/Fred_Again). Prominent UK DJs include [Judge Jules](/Judge_Jules), [Pete Tong](/Pete_Tong), [Carl Cox](/Carl_Cox), [Paul Oakenfold](/Paul_Oakenfold), [John Digweed](/John_Digweed), and [Sasha](/Sasha_(dj)).

***

#### Visual Art

Notable British artists include the [Romantic](/Romanticism) painters [William Blake](/William_Blake), [John Constable](/John_Constable), [Samuel Palmer](/Samuel_Palmer), and [J. M. W. Turner](/J._M._W._Turner); portrait painters such as [Sir Joshua Reynolds](/Joshua_Reynolds) and [Lucian Freud](/Lucian_Freud); landscape artists like [Thomas Gainsborough](/Thomas_Gainsborough) and [L. S. Lowry](/L._S._Lowry); [William Morris](/William_Morris), a pioneer of the [Arts and Crafts movement](/Arts_and_Crafts_movement); the figurative painter [Francis Bacon](/Francis_Bacon_(artist)); [Pop artists](/Pop_artist) including [Peter Blake](/Peter_Blake_(artist)), [Richard Hamilton](/Richard_Hamilton_(artist)), and [David Hockney](/David_Hockney); conceptual art pioneers [Art & Language](/Art_%26_Language); the collaborative duo [Gilbert and George](/Gilbert_and_George); abstract artist [Howard Hodgkin](/Howard_Hodgkin); and sculptors such as [Antony Gormley](/Antony_Gormley), [Anish Kapoor](/Anish_Kapoor), and [Henry Moore](/Henry_Moore). During the late 1980s and 1990s, the [Saatchi Gallery](/Saatchi_Gallery) in London played a key role in bringing to public attention a group of multi-genre artists known as the "[Young British Artists](/Young_British_Artists)," including [Damien Hirst](/Damien_Hirst), [Chris Ofili](/Chris_Ofili), [Rachel Whiteread](/Rachel_Whiteread), [Tracey Emin](/Tracey_Emin), [Mark Wallinger](/Mark_Wallinger), [Steve McQueen](/Steve_McQueen_(director)), [Sam Taylor-Wood](/Sam_Taylor-Wood), and the [Chapman Brothers](/Jake_and_Dinos_Chapman).

The [Royal Academy](/Royal_Academy) in London is a principal institution for the promotion of visual arts in the UK. Leading art schools include the six-school [University of the Arts London](/University_of_the_Arts_London), which comprises [Central Saint Martins College of Art and Design](/Central_Saint_Martins_College_of_Art_and_Design) and [Chelsea College of Art and Design](/Chelsea_College_of_Art_and_Design); [Goldsmiths, University of London](/Goldsmiths,_University_of_London); the [Slade School of Fine Art](/Slade_School_of_Fine_Art) (affiliated with [University College London](/University_College_London)); the [Glasgow School of Art](/Glasgow_School_of_Art); the [Royal College of Art](/Royal_College_of_Art); and [The Ruskin School of Drawing and Fine Art](/The_Ruskin_School_of_Drawing_and_Fine_Art) (part of the University of Oxford). The [Courtauld Institute of Art](/Courtauld_Institute_of_Art) is a distinguished center for the study of the [history of art](/History_of_art). Major art galleries in the UK include the [National Gallery](/National_Gallery), [National Portrait Gallery](/National_Portrait_Gallery_(London)), [Tate Britain](/Tate_Britain), and [Tate Modern](/Tate_Modern), which is the world's most visited modern art gallery, attracting approximately 4.7 million visitors annually. The sculpture [Angel of the North](/Angel_of_the_North) by [Antony Gormley](/Antony_Gormley) has become a symbolic representation of [Northern England](/Northern_England).

***

#### Cinema

The United Kingdom has exerted a considerable influence on the history of cinema. British directors such as [Alfred Hitchcock](/Alfred_Hitchcock), whose film [Vertigo](/Vertigo_(film)) is considered by some critics to be the [best film of all time](/List_of_films_considered_the_best), and [David Lean](/David_Lean), director of [Lawrence of Arabia](/Lawrence_of_Arabia_(film)), are among the most critically acclaimed filmmakers ever. More recent prominent directors include [Christopher Nolan](/Christopher_Nolan), [Sam Mendes](/Sam_Mendes), [Steve McQueen](/Steve_McQueen_(director)), [Richard Curtis](/Richard_Curtis), [Danny Boyle](/Danny_Boyle), [Tony Scott](/Tony_Scott), and [Ridley Scott](/Ridley_Scott). Many British actors have achieved international fame and critical recognition. Some of the most commercially successful films have originated from the United Kingdom, including two of the [highest-grossing film franchises](/List_of_highest-grossing_film_series): [Harry Potter](/Harry_Potter_(film_series)) and [James Bond](/James_Bond_(film_series)).

2019 proved to be a particularly strong year for British films, grossing approximately £10.3 billion globally and accounting for 28.7% of worldwide box office revenue. UK box-office takings reached £1.25 billion in 2019, with around 176 million admissions. In 2023, the available film and television studio stage space in the UK stood at 6.9 million sq ft, with an additional 1 million sq ft added in the preceding year and further expansion planned. The annual [BAFTA Film Awards](/British_Academy_Film_Awards) are presented by the [British Academy of Film and Television Arts](/British_Academy_of_Film_and_Television_Arts).

***

#### Cuisine

British cuisine has evolved through influences reflecting the nation's geography, historical settlements, arrivals of new populations and immigrants, trade, and colonial history. Historically, English food has been characterized by a straightforward approach and a reliance on the high quality of its natural produce. The traditional [Sunday roast](/Sunday_roast) exemplifies this, featuring a roasted joint (typically beef, lamb, chicken, or pork), often [free range](/Free_range) and generally grass-fed in the case of beef. Roasts are served with roasted or boiled vegetables, [Yorkshire pudding](/Yorkshire_pudding), and [gravy](/Gravy). Other traditional meals include [meat pies](/Meat_pie) and [stews](/Stew). A 2019 poll by [YouGov](/YouGov) rated classic British foods highly, with over 80% expressing fondness for the Sunday roast, Yorkshire pudding, [fish and chips](/Fish_and_chips), [crumpets](/Crumpet), and the [full English breakfast](/Full_English_breakfast).

The UK is home to a significant number of [fine dining](/Fine_dining) establishments. In 2025, there were 197 restaurants awarded a [Michelin Star](/Michelin_Star), with 55 of them categorizing their cuisine as 'Modern British.' Sweet dishes are prevalent in British cuisine, and a comprehensive list of [British desserts](/List_of_British_desserts) exists. Afternoon tea, a light meal served with tea in tearooms and hotels across the United Kingdom, dates back to approximately 1840. A July 2024 poll indicated that 3% of the UK population follows a [vegan](/Vegan) diet, 6% are [vegetarian](/Vegetarian), and 13% identify as [flexitarian](/Flexitarian) (adhering to a primarily vegetarian diet). The influence of the British Empire facilitated the introduction of [Indian cuisine](/Indian_cuisine) to Britain, known for its "strong, penetrating spices and herbs." British cuisine has integrated the cultural influences of immigrants, resulting in hybrid dishes such as [chicken tikka masala](/Chicken_tikka_masala). The British public has embraced global cuisines and regularly consumes dishes or fast food from other European countries, the Caribbean, and Asia.

The UK boasts numerous [gastropubs](/Gastropub) and is recognized as the origin of various beer styles, including [pale ale](/Pale_ale), [India pale ale](/India_pale_ale), [bitter](/Bitter_(beer)), [brown ale](/Brown_ale), [porter](/Porter_(beer)), and [stout](/Stout). The number of [craft beers](/Craft_beer) and microbreweries has seen rapid expansion over the past two decades. Other popular alcoholic beverages produced in the UK include [Scotch whisky](/Scotch_whisky), [English wine](/Wine_from_the_United_Kingdom), [gin](/Gin), [perry](/Perry), and [cider](/Cider).

