#### Sport

[Association football](/Association_football), [tennis](/Tennis), [table tennis](/Table_tennis), [badminton](/Badminton), [rugby union](/Rugby_union), [rugby league](/Rugby_league), [rugby sevens](/Rugby_sevens), [golf](/Golf), [boxing](/Boxing), [netball](/Netball), [water polo](/Water_polo), [field hockey](/Field_hockey), [billiards](/English_billiards), [darts](/Darts), [rowing](/Rowing_(sport)), [rounders](/Rounders), and [cricket](/Cricket) either originated in the UK or were significantly developed there. The rules and codes for many modern sports were codified during the Victorian era. A 2003 poll indicated football as the most popular sport in the UK. England is recognized by [FIFA](/FIFA) as the birthplace of club football, and the [Football Association](/Football_Association) is the oldest of its kind, with the [rules of football](/Laws_of_the_Game_(association_football)) first drafted in 1863 by [Ebenezer Cobb Morley](/Ebenezer_Cobb_Morley). Each of the [Home Nations](/Home_Nations) – England, Scotland, Wales, and Northern Ireland – maintains its own football association, national team, and [league system](/League_system). Each is also an individual governing member of the [International Football Association Board](/International_Football_Association_Board) alongside FIFA. The English top division, the [Premier League](/Premier_League), is the most widely watched football league globally. The inaugural international football match was contested between [England](/England_national_football_team) and [Scotland](/Scotland_national_football_team) on 30 November 1872. England, Scotland, [Wales](/Wales_national_football_team), and [Northern Ireland](/Northern_Ireland_national_football_team) typically compete as separate entities in international competitions.

In 2003, rugby union was ranked as the second most popular sport in the UK. The sport originated at [Rugby School](/Rugby_School) in Warwickshire, and the [first rugby international](/1871_England_versus_Scotland_rugby_union_match) took place on 27 March 1871 between [England](/England_national_rugby_union_team) and [Scotland](/Scotland_national_rugby_union_team). England, Scotland, [Wales](/Wales_national_rugby_union_team), [Ireland](/Ireland_national_rugby_union_team), [France](/France_national_rugby_union_team), and [Italy](/Italy_national_rugby_union_team) compete in the [Six Nations Championship](/Six_Nations_Championship), the premier international rugby union tournament in the Northern Hemisphere. Sports governing bodies in [England](/Rugby_union_in_England), [Scotland](/Rugby_union_in_Scotland), [Wales](/Rugby_union_in_Wales), and [Ireland](/Rugby_union_in_Ireland) independently organize and regulate the sport. Every four years, the Home Nations form a combined team known as the [British and Irish Lions](/British_and_Irish_Lions), which undertakes tours to Australia, New Zealand, and